{"title_page": "If I Am President (2018 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If I Am President\n| image          = File:If I Am President Movie 2018.jpg|thumb\n| director       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| producer       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| writer         = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ayoola Ayolola]]|[[Joke Silva]]|[[Bimbo Manuel]]|Rekiya Atta|[[Uzee Usman]]|[[Rahama Sadau]]|[[Ivie Okujaye]]}}\n| cinematography = Ifeanyi Iloduba (BOKA)\n| editing        = Olamide Aremu (DOT COM)\n| studio         = High Definition Film Studio\n| promotions     = \n| distributor    = Genesis Cinemas \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|11|09}}\n| runtime        = 120mins\n| country        = Nigeria\n| language       = English, Igbo, Hausa & Yoruba\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| website            = {{URL|ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''''If I Am President''''' is a 2018 Nigerian political thriller film written, produced and directed by Bright Wonder Obasi, starring [[Ayoola Ayolola]], [[Joke Silva]], [[Bimbo Manuel]], [[Rahama Sadau]], [[Ivie Okujaye]], Rekiya Atta, [[Uzee Usman]]. It won award for Best Screenplay at the 2019 Motion Pictures International Film Festival (MOPIFF)<ref>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QwZ8PQaYISu_0n0_zLy4y1KXHLvsCwAw/view</ref>.\n\n==Plot==\nSet in the present-day political terrain and discourses in Nigeria, \u201cIf I Am President\u201d tells the story of 37-year old ZinachiOhams, the presidential candidate of the Nigerian Rebirth Party, a new party made up of young idealists and recently metamorphosed from a Civil Society Organization. The group make a push into the murky and rough political terrain, armed with little more than their ideals, and wade through challenges of nasty politically engineered attacks, to emerge as the party and candidate to beat in the oncoming elections.\n\n[[File:IIAP movie poster.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ayoola Ayolola]] as Zina\n*[[Joke Silva]] as \n*Rekiya Atta as\n*[[Bimbo Manuel]] as Maurice\n*[[Rahama Sadau]]\n*[[Ivie Okujaye]] as\n*[[Bryan Okwara]] as\n*[[Uzee Usman]] as \n*Sydney Diala as\n*Ayo Emmanuel as\n*Norman Doo Moor as \n*[[Chimdiya Nwigwe]] as \n*[[Adaora Onyechere]] as Anchor\n*[[Rachel Bakam]] TV Presenter\n*Victor Decka\n*Osas Iyamu\t\t\t\n\n==Tagline==\nToday is the tomorrow we prayed for yesterday!\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nigerian films of 2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://http://www.ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Nigerian films]]\n[[Category:Films by Nigerian directors]]\n[[Category:Nigerian drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If I Am President\n| image          = File:If I Am President Movie 2018.jpg|thumb\n| director       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| producer       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| writer         = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ayoola Ayolola]]|[[Joke Silva]]|[[Bimbo Manuel]]|Rekiya Atta|[[Uzee Usman]]|[[Rahama Sadau]]|[[Ivie Okujaye]]}}\n| cinematography = Ifeanyi Iloduba (BOKA)\n| editing        = Olamide Aremu (DOT COM)\n| studio         = High Definition Film Studio\n| promotions     = Virtues & Nobletouch Nigeria [[vntmedia]]\n| distributor    = Genesis Cinemas \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|11|09}}\n| runtime        = 120mins\n| country        = Nigeria\n| language       = English, Igbo, Hausa & Yoruba\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| website        = {{url|ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''''If I Am President''''' is a 2018 Nigerian political thriller film written, produced and directed by Bright Wonder Obasi, starring [[Ayoola Ayolola]], [[Joke Silva]], [[Bimbo Manuel]], [[Rahama Sadau]], [[Ivie Okujaye]], Rekiya Atta, [[Uzee Usman]]. It won award for Best Screenplay at the 2019 Motion Pictures International Film Festival (MOPIFF)<ref>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QwZ8PQaYISu_0n0_zLy4y1KXHLvsCwAw/view</ref>.\n\n==Plot==\nSet in the present-day political terrain and discourses in Nigeria, \u201cIf I Am President\u201d tells the story of 37-year old ZinachiOhams, the presidential candidate of the Nigerian Rebirth Party, a new party made up of young idealists and recently metamorphosed from a Civil Society Organization. The group make a push into the murky and rough political terrain, armed with little more than their ideals, and wade through challenges of nasty politically engineered attacks, to emerge as the party and candidate to beat in the oncoming elections.\n\n[[File:IIAP movie poster.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ayoola Ayolola]] as Zina\n*[[Joke Silva]] as \n*Rekiya Atta as\n*[[Bimbo Manuel]] as Maurice\n*[[Rahama Sadau]]\n*[[Ivie Okujaye]] as\n*[[Bryan Okwara]] as\n*[[Uzee Usman]] as \n*Sydney Diala as\n*Ayo Emmanuel as\n*Norman Doo Moor as \n*[[Chimdiya Nwigwe]] as \n*[[Adaora Onyechere]] as Anchor\n*[[Rachel Bakam]] TV Presenter\n*Victor Decka\n*Osas Iyamu\t\t\t\n\n==Tagline==\nToday is the tomorrow we prayed for yesterday!\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nigerian films of 2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://http://www.ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Nigerian films]]\n[[Category:Films by Nigerian directors]]\n[[Category:Nigerian drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Nnadi Duke", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_I_Am_President_(2018_film)"}
{"title_page": "Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=October 2014}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2010}}\n{{Contradicts other|Abdul Majed|here|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title= Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman\n|image=The Father of The Nation places in gopalganj.JPG\n|caption=\n|location=[[Dhaka]], Bangladesh\n|target=[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] and his family\n|date=15 August 1975\n|time=5.30am\u20137:00&nbsp;am.\n|timezone=\n|type=[[Military coup]]\n|fatalities=20 (including Sheikh Mujib, his wife, and 3 sons){{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed to confirm the number|date=October 2017}}\n|injuries=2\n|perps=[[Syed Faruque Rahman]], Khandaker Abdur Rashid, [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]], Mohiuddin Ahmed, A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed, Shariful Haq (Dalim) Noor\n|motive=Perceived failure of the authoritarian [[Bangladeshi government]] and its subservience to India}}\n\nThe first [[president of Bangladesh]] [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] (also known as Sheikh Mujib or just Mujib or Bangabandhu) and almost his entire family were killed during the early hours of 15 August 1975, when a group of young [[Bangladesh Army]] personnel went into his residence and assassinated Sheikh Mujib as part of [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat|a coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n\n==Background==\n{{further|History of Bangladesh}}\n\n===Mujib's presidency===\nIn the [[1970 Pakistani general election]], Sheikh Mujib's party, the [[Awami League]], won the majority of the seats in the [[Pakistani National Assembly]]. They won 167 of the 169 seats in East Pakistan, which would later become Bangladesh after it seceded from West Pakistan. Despite Pakistan's military government delaying the handover of power, Mujib's house had become the de facto head of government in East Pakistan by March. At the start of the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in 1971, he was arrested in his home by Pakistani soldiers. Later that year the provisional government of the Bangladeshi rebellion, the [[Mujibnagar Government]], formed on 10 April and made Mujib its head and also the leader of Bangladeshi armed forces.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last=Harun-or-Rashid |year=2012 |chapter=Rahman, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Rahman,_Bangabandhu_Sheikh_Mujibur |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> Following the independence of Bangladesh on 16 December 1971, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was released from custody from Pakistan in [[London]], and flew to India followed by Bangladesh. Mujib led the government as [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]] of Bangladesh for three years after Bangladesh gained independence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHe was later elected [[President of Bangladesh|President]] of Bangladesh and established a national unity government, the [[Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League]] (BAKSAL), on 7 June 1975 by banning all political parties and independent press. Although the BAKSAL was intended to bring stability to Bangladesh and uphold law and order, it engendered hostility among the bureaucracy, military, and civil society. Opposition groups, as well as some of Mujib's supporters, challenged Mujib's authoritarian, one-party state.<ref>{{cite book |last=Islam |first=Sirajul |year=2012 |chapter=Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bangladesh_Krishak_Sramik_Awami_League |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> The period of the BAKSAL's one-party rule was marked by widespread censorship and abuse of the judiciary, as well as opposition from the general populace, intellectuals, and all other political groups.<ref name=\":1\" /> The country was in chaos: corruption was rampant, and food shortage and poor distribution led to a disastrous famine. Nationalization of industry failed to yield any tangible progress. Not only was the government weak and with no clear goals, but the country was also nearly bankrupt. In the ''[[Far Eastern Economic Review]]'', journalist Lawrence Lifschultz wrote in 1974 that \"the corruption and malpractices and plunder of national wealth\" in Bangladesh were \"unprecedented\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last=Datta-Ray |first=Sunanda K. |date=6 February 2010 |title=Tread Warily to the Dream |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100206/jsp/opinion/story_12065942.jsp |work=The Telegraph |location=Calcutta, India |type=Opinion}}</ref>\n\n===Left-wing insurgency===\nA left-wing insurgency from 1972 to 1975 is widely held responsible for creating the conditions that led up to the assassination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Awami League will have to atone for making a JaSoD leader minister, says Syed Ashraf |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2016/06/13/awami-league-will-have-to-atone-for-making-a-jasod-leader-minister-says-syed-ashraf |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=13 June 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Clarify your role in Bangabandhu killing, BNP to Inu |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/76721/No-lecture-on-democracy-please-BNP-to-Inu |newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]] |date=24 August 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012181457/http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/76721/No-lecture-on-democracy-please-BNP-to-Inu |archive-date=12 October 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No law of 'illegitimate govt' will last, says Khaleda |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2014/08/25/no-law-of-illegitimate-govt-will-last-says-khaleda |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=25 August 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> In 1972, a leftist group named the [[Jatiya Samajtantrik Dal]] (JSD) was founded from a split in the [[Bangladesh Chhatra League]], the student wing of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hossain |first1=Kazi Mobarak |title=Hasanul Haq Inu's JaSoD splits as he names Shirin general secretary |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2016/03/12/hasanul-haq-inus-jasod-splits-as-he-names-shirin-general-secretary |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=13 March 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> They had an ideology of [[scientific socialism]]. The JSD, through its armed wing [[Gonobahini]] led by Colonel [[Abu Taher]] and politician [[Hasanul Haq Inu]], began a political massacre of government supporters, [[Awami League]] members, and police.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=JS sees debate over role of Gono Bahini |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/js-sees-debate-over-role-of-gono-bahini-31691 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inu, Khairul to be tried in people's court: BNP |url=http://www.newstoday.com.bd/index.php?option=details&news_id=2434364&date=2016-02-03 |newspaper=The News Today |agency=UNB |date=15 June 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> Their campaign contributed to a breakdown of law and order in the country<ref name=\":0\" /> and paved the way for the assassination of Mujib.<ref>{{cite news |title=JSD, NAP, left parties also behind the killing of Bangabandhu |url=http://thedailynewnation.com/news/64702/jsd-nap-left-parties-also-behind-the-killing-of-bangabandhu.html |newspaper=The New Nation |date=26 August 2015 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Conspirators===\nMajor [[Syed Faruque Rahman]]; [[Khandaker Abdur Rashid]]; [[Shariful Haque Dalim]]; and [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]], along with A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed, Bazlul Huda, and S.&nbsp;H.&nbsp;M.&nbsp;B. Noor Chowdhury (three majors in the [[Bangladesh Army]] and veterans of the Bangladesh Liberation War), planned to topple the government and establish a military government of their own. They were previously part of the opposition to BAKSAL and viewed the government as too subservient to India and a threat to Bangladesh's military.<ref>{{cite news |title=Farooq's confession |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/farooqs-confession-1269634 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]], an Awami League cabinet minister under Mujib's government, agreed to take over the Presidency. Journalist Lawrence Lifschultz paints an alternate picture of the conspiracy, however, that implicates Mostaq and the US [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA). In his book ''Bangladesh: The Unfinished Revolution'', he wrote that the \"CIA station chief in Dhaka, Philip Cherry, was actively involved in the killing of the Father of the Nation\u2014Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.\"<ref>[http://www.daily-sun.com/post/66979/Long-shadow-of-the-August-1975-coup Long shadow of the August 1975 coup]. ''[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]]'', 14 August 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Nagarajan |first=K. V. |date=September 1982 |title=Review: Bangladesh: The Unfinished Revolution by Lawrence Lifschultz |url= |journal=The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science |publisher=Sage Publications |volume=463 |pages=169\u2013170 |jstor=1043636}}</ref><ref>[http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/08/15/d5081501033.htm The past is never dead - The long shadow of the August 1975 coup]. By Lawrence Lifschultz. ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'', vol. 5 # 434, 15 August 2005.</ref> It is alleged that the Chief of Army Staff, Major General [[K M Shafiullah|Kazi Mohammed Shafiullah]], and the [[Directorate General of Forces Intelligence]] Air Vice Marshal, Aminul Islam Khan, were aware of the conspiracy.<ref>[http://www.akhonsamoy.com/back/Vol10/102/pages/Page_01.htm Ziaur Rahman informed Sheikh Mujibur Rahman earlier about coup threat] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605203008/http://www.akhonsamoy.com/back/Vol10/102/pages/Page_01.htm |date=5 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Assassination===\nIn the early morning of 15 August 1975, the conspirators divided into four groups. One group, consisting of members of the Bengal Lancers of the First Armoured Division and 535th Infantry Division under Major Huda, attacked Mujib's residence.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=63\u201364}}: \"According to foreign journalists, the operation started at 12.30 A.M. ... divided into four groups. The first group rolled towards Mujib's residence ... The first group was formed with selected soldiers from the Bengal Lancers of the First Armoured Division and 535 Infantry Regiment. It was put under Major Huda. \"</ref> Correspondent for ''[[Anandabazar Patrika]]'' Sukharanjan Dasgupta, who described the Bangladesh Liberation War in Dhaka until 1974, writes in his book ''Midnight Massacre in Dacca'' that \"the exact details of the massacre will always remain shrouded in mystery.\"<ref name=\"Dasgupta1978p64\" /> He goes on to say, however, that the army platoon protecting the president's house offered no resistance. [[Sheikh Kamal]], son of Mujib, was shot at the reception area on the ground floor.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=65\u201366}}: \"[soldiers] quickly surrounded Mujib's residence. A couple of rounds were fired. No resistance came from the army platoon guarding the President's house ... The first round of fire had brought Sheikh Kamal hurrying down to the reception on the ground floor ... A short burst, and his body, riddled with bullets sank to the floor.\"</ref> Meanwhile, Mujib was asked to resign and allowed time to consider his choice. He telephoned Colonel [[Jamil Uddin Ahmad]], the new Chief of Military Intelligence. When Jamil arrived and ordered the troops back to the barracks, he was gunned down at the gate of the residence. After he refused to resign, Mujib was shot and killed.<ref name=\"Dasgupta1978p64\">{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 2}}: \"Reports reveal that they did not kill Sheikh Mujib at once. Mujib was asked to step down from power and he was given some time to decide. Mujib summoned Colonel Jamil, the new chief of the Military Intelligence over the phone. Colonel Jamil arrived fast and ordered the army to return to the barracks ... Then a rapid burst from machine guns mowed down Jamil right in front of the gate.\"</ref>\n\nOther people killed in the attack were [[Sheikh Fazilatunnesa Mujib]], wife of Mujib, who was killed upstairs; [[Sheikh Nasser]], younger brother of Mujib, who was killed in a lavatory; several servants of Mujib, who were also killed in lavatories; [[Sheikh Jamal]], the second son of Mujib and an army officer; ten-year-old [[Sheikh Russel]], the youngest son of Mujib; and two daughters-in-law of Mujib.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|p=67}}: \"The murderers rushed upstairs ... they came across Begum Lutfunnessa Mujib ... Shots rang out again. Begum Mujib lay on the floor, dead ... A group searched the ground floor. In the lavatories, they found Sheikh Nasser and a couple of servants and gunned them down. The other group charged into Mujib's bedroom. There they found the two daughters-in-law of Mujib along with Sheikh Jamal and Sheikh Russel ... they, too, were not spared by these butchers.\"</ref> \n\nIn [[Dhanmondi]], two other groups of soldiers killed [[Sheikh Fazlul Haque Mani]], Mujib's nephew and a leader of the Awami League along with his pregnant wife, Arzu Moni, and [[Abdur Rab Serniabat]], Mujib's brother-in-law. They also killed a minister of the government and thirteen of his family members on Mintu Road.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|p=65}}: \"Lieutenant Moalemuddin sped for the residence of Sheikh Mani with three trucks full of soldiers ... while Major Shahriar and Captain Huda went out with some soldiers to get rid of Minister Abdur Rab Sarniabat.\"</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 3}}: \"At the same time at 13/1 Dhanmandi Sheikh Fazlul Haq and his pregnant wife, and on Mineta Road, Abdur Rab Sarniabat with the 13 members of his family, were butchered ...\"</ref>\n\nThe fourth and most powerful group was sent towards Savar to repel the expected counter-attack by the security forces stationed there. After a brief fight and the loss of eleven men, the security forces surrendered.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 1}}: \"[The] fourth group, the most powerful of the lot, proceeded towards Savar, near Dacca, to repel the anticipated counter-attack by the Security Forces. It did run against some resistance at Savar. But once the shelling took toll of eleven people, the leaderless Security Force surrendered\"</ref>\n\nFour of the founding leaders of the Awami League, first Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Tajuddin Ahmed]], former Prime Minister [[Mansur Ali]], former Vice President [[Syed Nazrul Islam]], and former Home Minister [[A.&nbsp;H.&nbsp;M. Qamaruzzaman]], were arrested. Three months later, on 3 November 1975, they [[Jail Killing Day|were murdered]] in [[Dhaka Central Jail]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=77\u201378}}: \"3 November ... Khondakar also knew that the situation was bound to be grave once Nazrul Islam, Tajuddin Ahmed, Kamaruzzaman and Mansur Ali were released ... Khondakar had had them arrested under various pretexts shortly after Mujib's assassination, and they were still rotting in Dacca Jail. So, Khondakar ... managed to allow the associates of the \"killers\" [the seven Majors who assassinated Sheikh Mujibur Rahman] inside the jail to brutally kill these four leaders.\"</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of assassination===\n[[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]] assumed the presidency, and [[Major General]] [[Ziaur Rahman]] became the new Chief of Army Staff. The leading conspirators were all given high government ranks. They were all later toppled by yet another coup led by [[Brigadier General]] [[Khaled Mosharraf]] on 3 November 1975. Mosharraf himself was killed during a counter-revolt four days later on 7 November, which freed Major General Ziaur Rahman in power and was brought in to bring law and order. \n\nMajor [[Syed Faruque Rahman]], Rashid, and the other army officers were promoted to the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]]. Nevertheless, they were exiled to [[Libyan Arab Republic|Libya]], China, [[Rhodesia]], Canada, and other countries, although they were given several diplomatic posts in Bangladeshi missions abroad. Lieutenant Colonel (Rtd.) Syed Faruque Rahman later returned and founded the [[Bangladesh Freedom Party]] in 1985 and took part in the presidential election in 1987 against the military ruler [[Lieutenant General]] [[Hussain Mohammad Ershad]] but lost that election in a landslide.\n\nMujib's two daughters, [[Sheikh Hasina]] and [[Sheikh Rehana]], were in [[West Germany]] at the time of his assassination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladeshi PM Sheikh Hasina requests extradition of Bangabandhu killers from US |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/international/bangladeshi-pm-sheikh-hasina-requests-extradition-of-bangabandhu-killers-from-us-116083000733_1.html |newspaper=Business Standard |agency=Press Trust of India |date=30 August 2016 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> After the coup, they flew back to India, instead of Bangladesh and took refuge with the Indian government. Sheikh Hasina lived in New Delhi in a self-imposed exile before returning to Bangladesh on 17 May 1981.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ahmed |first=Helal Uddin |year=2012 |chapter=Hasina, Sheikh |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Hasina,_Sheikh |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>\n\n===Trial===\nThe military decided not to [[court-martial]] the military officers who masterminded and participated in the coup. [[AFM Mohitul Islam|A.&nbsp;F.&nbsp;M. Mohitul Islam]], personal assistant to Sheikh Mujib and a survivor of the attack on his house, attempted to file a case against the military officers, but the police slapped him in the face and refused to file the report.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ordeals of plaintiff |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/ordeals-plaintiff-1269652 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> The assassination conspirators could not be tried in a court of law because of the [[Indemnity Act, Bangladesh|Indemnity Act]] passed by the government under President [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]]. When the Awami League, led by Mujib's daughter [[Sheikh Hasina]], won elections in 1996, the act was repealed. The Bangabandhu murder trial began with the case filing by A.&nbsp;F.&nbsp;M. Mohitul Islam.<ref name=\"hfxb\">{{cite news |title=Mohitul Islam passes away |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/mohitul-islam-passes-away-1275547 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=26 August 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nColonel (Rtd.) [[Syed Faruque Rahman]] was arrested from his Dhaka home, and Colonel (Rtd.) [[Bazlul Huda]] was brought back from [[Bangkok]], where he was serving a prison sentence for [[shop lifting|shoplifting]] as part of a criminal exchange program between [[Thailand]] and Bangladesh. Lieutenant Colonel [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]] was in active military service when he was arrested. Colonel (Rtd.) [[Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan]] had been appointed to active diplomatic service by previous Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Begum Khaleda Zia]], but he returned to Bangladesh and was arrested when he was recalled by the foreign ministry. Colonel (Rtd.) [[Abdur Rashid]] and other accused individuals had already left Bangladesh, however. They believed that the upcoming 1996 general election would be an Awami League victory, which would result in the repealing of the Indemnity Act and their subsequent arrest. Colonel (Rtd.) Rashid now reportedly shuttles between Pakistan and Libya. All these men were also involved in [[Jail Killing Day]] on 3 November 1975, when four Awami League officials were assassinated.{{citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\nThe first trial ended on 8 November 1998. The District and Session Judge of Dhaka, Mohammad Golam Rasul, ordered the death sentence by firing squad to fifteen out of the twenty accused of conspiring in the assassination. The sentences were not carried out immediately, because five of the convicts sought to file appeals in the high court division of the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]]. The Supreme Court, consisting of Justice Mohammad Ruhul Amin and Justice A.&nbsp;B.&nbsp;M. Khairul Haque, who was the former [[Chief Justice of Bangladesh]], gave a divisive verdict. Senior Justice Amin acquitted five out of the original fifteen accused, whereas Junior Justice Haque upheld the lower court's verdict. A verdict from a third judge became necessary. Later, Justice Mohammad Fazlul Karim condemned twelve out of original fifteen, including two acquitted in Justice Amin's verdict. \n\nOne of the convicts, Major (Rtd.) Aziz Pasha died in Zimbabwe on 2 June 2001.<ref>[http://www.peoplesmouth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7220:6-killers-still-out-of-reach&catid=34:jv-slideshow 6 killers still out of reach]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221162331/http://www.peoplesmouth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7220%3A6-killers-still-out-of-reach&catid=34%3Ajv-slideshow |date=21 February 2014 }}</ref> Although the five accused appealed to the [[Law of Bangladesh#The Appellate Division|appellate division of the Supreme Court]], their decision remained pending from August 2001. Several judges refused to hear the case, which meant the government lacked the three judges required to hold a hearing session. On 18 June 2007, one of the conspirators who had been sentenced to death, Major (Rtd.) A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed was extradited to Bangladesh from the United States following a series of failed attempts to gain [[right of asylum|asylum]] or [[permanent residency]] in the United States. On 7 August 2007, the murder case hearings resumed after a six year delay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu murder case hearing resumes today after 6 years |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/08/07/d7080701033.htm |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=7 August 2007}}</ref> The appellate division of the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]] gave its verdict on 19 November 2009,<ref>''Major Md. Bazlul Huda (Artillery) & Ors. vs. The State'', [http://www.supremecourt.gov.bd/scweb/documents/325397_judgements1.pdf Criminal Appeal Nos. 55\u201359 of 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922200140/http://www.supremecourt.gov.bd/scweb/documents/325397_judgements1.pdf |date=22 September 2013 }}</ref> after a five-member special bench, headed by Justice Mahammad Tafazzal Islam, spent 29 days hearing the petition filed by the convicted.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite news |title=Mujib murder case appeals verdict today |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802230939/http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |archive-date=2 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Security tightened around SC |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=114637 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe appeal of the convicts was rejected, and the death sentence was upheld.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title=Bangladesh officers lose appeal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8366329.stm |work=BBC News |date=19 November 2009}}</ref> Before the verdict, approximately 12,000 extra policemen were deployed to guard strategic buildings, including the Supreme Court building, to prevent disruption of the proceedings by the convicted men's supporters.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Nevertheless, they were blamed by the government for a grenade attack on one of the prosecution lawyers in October 2009, although no one has been charged yet.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nCaptain (Rtd.) [[Qismet Hashem]], Captain (Rtd.) [[Nazmul Hossain Aanssar]], and Major (Rtd.) [[Abdul Majid (officer)|Abdul Majid]] were acquitted through the high court division and appellate division verdicts and now live in Canada. [[Taheruddin Thakur]], former Information Minister and one of the suspects, was cleared during the Hasina Government, acquitted in trial, and released. He died naturally in 2009.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite news |title=Mujib murder case appeals verdict today |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802230939/http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |archive-date=2 August 2010}}</ref> Conspirators Major (Rtd.) Bazlul Huda, Lieutenant Colonel (Rtd.) Mohiuddin Ahmed, Major (Rtd.) [[A.K.M. Mohiuddin Ahmed|A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed]], Colonel (Rtd.) [[Syed Faruque Rahman]], and Colonel (Rtd.) Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan was executed on 28 January 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ahmed |first=Anis |date=27 January 2010 |title=Bangladesh Hangs Killers of Independence Leader Mujib |newspaper=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE60Q67320100127}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |author=Charlie Gillis |date=15 February 2011 |title=The assassin among us \u2013 Nur Chowdhury faces execution for killing Bangladesh's president. That's why he's safe in Canada. |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/02/15/the-assassin-among-us-2/ |magazine=[[Maclean's]]}}</ref>\nOn 11 April 2020 Abdul Masjed was executed by hanging. He had returned to Bangladesh the previous month after being a fugitive for 23 years.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52258557</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[BAKSAL]]\n* [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Dasgupta |first=Sukharanjan |title=Midnight Massacre in Dacca |year=1978 |location=New Delhi |publisher=Vikas |isbn=0-7069-0692-6 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Coord|23.7517|N|90.3767|E|region:BD_type:event|display=title}}\n{{Sheikh Mujibur Rahman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rahman}}\n[[Category:1975 crimes in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:1975 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:1975 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:1970s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1970s mass shootings in Asia]]\n[[Category:1990s trials]]\n[[Category:20th century in Dhaka]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman| ]]\n[[Category:August 1975 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1975 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1975]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Bangladesh]]\n<!--[[Category:Mass shootings in Bangladesh]]-->\n[[Category:Military coups in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Murder in Dhaka]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n[[Category:Trials in Bangladesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=October 2014}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2010}}\n{{Contradicts other|Abdul Majed|here|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title= Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman\n|image=The Father of The Nation places in gopalganj.JPG\n|caption=\n|location=[[Dhaka]], Bangladesh\n|target=[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] and his family\n|date=15 August 1975\n|time=5.30am\u20137:00&nbsp;am.\n|timezone=\n|type=[[Military coup]]\n|fatalities=20 (including Sheikh Mujib, his wife, and 3 sons){{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed to confirm the number|date=October 2017}}\n|injuries=2\n|perps=[[Syed Faruque Rahman]], Khandaker Abdur Rashid, [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]], Mohiuddin Ahmed, A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed, Shariful Haq (Dalim) Noor\n|motive=Perceived failure of the authoritarian [[Bangladeshi government]] and its subservience to India}}\n\nThe first [[president of Bangladesh]] [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] (also known as Sheikh Mujib or just Mujib or Bangabandhu) and almost his entire family were killed during the early hours of 15 August 1975, when a group of young [[Bangladesh Army]] personnel went into his residence and assassinated Sheikh Mujib as part of [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat|a coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n\n==Background==\n{{further|History of Bangladesh}}\n\n===Mujib's presidency===\nIn the [[1970 Pakistani general election]], Sheikh Mujib's party, the [[Awami League]], won the majority of the seats in the [[Pakistani National Assembly]]. They won 167 of the 169 seats in East Pakistan, which would later become Bangladesh after it seceded from West Pakistan. Despite Pakistan's military government delaying the handover of power, Mujib's house had become the de facto head of government in East Pakistan by March. At the start of the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in 1971, he was arrested in his home by Pakistani soldiers. Later that year the provisional government of the Bangladeshi rebellion, the [[Mujibnagar Government]], formed on 10 April and made Mujib its head and also the leader of Bangladeshi armed forces.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last=Harun-or-Rashid |year=2012 |chapter=Rahman, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Rahman,_Bangabandhu_Sheikh_Mujibur |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> Following the independence of Bangladesh on 16 December 1971, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was released from custody from Pakistan in [[London]], and flew to India followed by Bangladesh. Mujib led the government as [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]] of Bangladesh for three years after Bangladesh gained independence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHe was later elected [[President of Bangladesh|President]] of Bangladesh and established a national unity government, the [[Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League]] (BAKSAL), on 7 June 1975 by banning all political parties and independent press. Although the BAKSAL was intended to bring stability to Bangladesh and uphold law and order, it engendered hostility among the bureaucracy, military, and civil society. Opposition groups, as well as some of Mujib's supporters, challenged Mujib's authoritarian, one-party state.<ref>{{cite book |last=Islam |first=Sirajul |year=2012 |chapter=Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bangladesh_Krishak_Sramik_Awami_League |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> The period of the BAKSAL's one-party rule was marked by widespread censorship and abuse of the judiciary, as well as opposition from the general populace, intellectuals, and all other political groups.<ref name=\":1\" /> The country was in chaos: corruption was rampant, and food shortage and poor distribution led to a disastrous famine. Nationalization of industry failed to yield any tangible progress. Not only was the government weak and with no clear goals, but the country was also nearly bankrupt. In the ''[[Far Eastern Economic Review]]'', journalist Lawrence Lifschultz wrote in 1974 that \"the corruption and malpractices and plunder of national wealth\" in Bangladesh were \"unprecedented\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last=Datta-Ray |first=Sunanda K. |date=6 February 2010 |title=Tread Warily to the Dream |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100206/jsp/opinion/story_12065942.jsp |work=The Telegraph |location=Calcutta, India |type=Opinion}}</ref>\n\n===Left-wing insurgency===\nA left-wing insurgency from 1972 to 1975 is widely held responsible for creating the conditions that led up to the assassination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Awami League will have to atone for making a JaSoD leader minister, says Syed Ashraf |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2016/06/13/awami-league-will-have-to-atone-for-making-a-jasod-leader-minister-says-syed-ashraf |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=13 June 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Clarify your role in Bangabandhu killing, BNP to Inu |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/76721/No-lecture-on-democracy-please-BNP-to-Inu |newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]] |date=24 August 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012181457/http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/76721/No-lecture-on-democracy-please-BNP-to-Inu |archive-date=12 October 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No law of 'illegitimate govt' will last, says Khaleda |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2014/08/25/no-law-of-illegitimate-govt-will-last-says-khaleda |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=25 August 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> In 1972, a leftist group named the [[Jatiya Samajtantrik Dal]] (JSD) was founded from a split in the [[Bangladesh Chhatra League]], the student wing of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hossain |first1=Kazi Mobarak |title=Hasanul Haq Inu's JaSoD splits as he names Shirin general secretary |url=http://bdnews24.com/politics/2016/03/12/hasanul-haq-inus-jasod-splits-as-he-names-shirin-general-secretary |newspaper=bdnews24.com |date=13 March 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> They had an ideology of [[scientific socialism]]. The JSD, through its armed wing [[Gonobahini]] led by Colonel [[Abu Taher]] and politician [[Hasanul Haq Inu]], began a political massacre of government supporters, [[Awami League]] members, and police.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=JS sees debate over role of Gono Bahini |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/js-sees-debate-over-role-of-gono-bahini-31691 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inu, Khairul to be tried in people's court: BNP |url=http://www.newstoday.com.bd/index.php?option=details&news_id=2434364&date=2016-02-03 |newspaper=The News Today |agency=UNB |date=15 June 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> Their campaign contributed to a breakdown of law and order in the country<ref name=\":0\" /> and paved the way for the assassination of Mujib.<ref>{{cite news |title=JSD, NAP, left parties also behind the killing of Bangabandhu |url=http://thedailynewnation.com/news/64702/jsd-nap-left-parties-also-behind-the-killing-of-bangabandhu.html |newspaper=The New Nation |date=26 August 2015 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Conspirators===\nMajor [[Syed Faruque Rahman]]; [[Khandaker Abdur Rashid]]; [[Shariful Haque Dalim]]; and [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]], along with A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed, Bazlul Huda, and S.&nbsp;H.&nbsp;M.&nbsp;B. Noor Chowdhury (three majors in the [[Bangladesh Army]] and veterans of the Bangladesh Liberation War), planned to topple the government and establish a military government of their own. They were previously part of the opposition to BAKSAL and viewed the government as too subservient to India and a threat to Bangladesh's military.<ref>{{cite news |title=Farooq's confession |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/farooqs-confession-1269634 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]], an Awami League cabinet minister under Mujib's government, agreed to take over the Presidency. Journalist Lawrence Lifschultz paints an alternate picture of the conspiracy, however, that implicates Mostaq and the US [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA). In his book ''Bangladesh: The Unfinished Revolution'', he wrote that the \"CIA station chief in Dhaka, Philip Cherry, was actively involved in the killing of the Father of the Nation\u2014Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.\"<ref>[http://www.daily-sun.com/post/66979/Long-shadow-of-the-August-1975-coup Long shadow of the August 1975 coup]. ''[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]]'', 14 August 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Nagarajan |first=K. V. |date=September 1982 |title=Review: Bangladesh: The Unfinished Revolution by Lawrence Lifschultz |url= |journal=The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science |publisher=Sage Publications |volume=463 |pages=169\u2013170 |jstor=1043636}}</ref><ref>[http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/08/15/d5081501033.htm The past is never dead - The long shadow of the August 1975 coup]. By Lawrence Lifschultz. ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'', vol. 5 # 434, 15 August 2005.</ref> It is alleged that the Chief of Army Staff, Major General [[K M Shafiullah|Kazi Mohammed Shafiullah]], and the [[Directorate General of Forces Intelligence]] Air Vice Marshal, Aminul Islam Khan, were aware of the conspiracy.<ref>[http://www.akhonsamoy.com/back/Vol10/102/pages/Page_01.htm Ziaur Rahman informed Sheikh Mujibur Rahman earlier about coup threat] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605203008/http://www.akhonsamoy.com/back/Vol10/102/pages/Page_01.htm |date=5 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Assassination===\nIn the early morning of 15 August 1975, the conspirators divided into four groups. One group, consisting of members of the Bengal Lancers of the First Armoured Division and 535th Infantry Division under Major Huda, attacked Mujib's residence.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=63\u201364}}: \"According to foreign journalists, the operation started at 12.30 A.M. ... divided into four groups. The first group rolled towards Mujib's residence ... The first group was formed with selected soldiers from the Bengal Lancers of the First Armoured Division and 535 Infantry Regiment. It was put under Major Huda. \"</ref> Correspondent for ''[[Anandabazar Patrika]]'' Sukharanjan Dasgupta, who described the Bangladesh Liberation War in Dhaka until 1974, writes in his book ''Midnight Massacre in Dacca'' that \"the exact details of the massacre will always remain shrouded in mystery.\"<ref name=\"Dasgupta1978p64\" /> He goes on to say, however, that the army platoon protecting the president's house offered no resistance. [[Sheikh Kamal]], son of Mujib, was shot at the reception area on the ground floor.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=65\u201366}}: \"[soldiers] quickly surrounded Mujib's residence. A couple of rounds were fired. No resistance came from the army platoon guarding the President's house ... The first round of fire had brought Sheikh Kamal hurrying down to the reception on the ground floor ... A short burst, and his body, riddled with bullets sank to the floor.\"</ref> Meanwhile, Mujib was asked to resign and allowed time to consider his choice. He telephoned Colonel [[Jamil Uddin Ahmad]], the new Chief of Military Intelligence. When Jamil arrived and ordered the troops back to the barracks, he was gunned down at the gate of the residence. After he refused to resign, Mujib was shot and killed.<ref name=\"Dasgupta1978p64\">{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 2}}: \"Reports reveal that they did not kill Sheikh Mujib at once. Mujib was asked to step down from power and he was given some time to decide. Mujib summoned Colonel Jamil, the new chief of the Military Intelligence over the phone. Colonel Jamil arrived fast and ordered the army to return to the barracks ... Then a rapid burst from machine guns mowed down Jamil right in front of the gate.\"</ref>\n\nOther people killed in the attack were [[Sheikh Fazilatunnesa Mujib]], wife of Mujib, who was killed upstairs; [[Sheikh Nasser]], younger brother of Mujib, who was killed in a lavatory; several servants of Mujib, who were also killed in lavatories; [[Sheikh Jamal]], the second son of Mujib and an army officer; ten-year-old [[Sheikh Russel]], the youngest son of Mujib; and two daughters-in-law of Mujib.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|p=67}}: \"The murderers rushed upstairs ... they came across Begum Lutfunnessa Mujib ... Shots rang out again. Begum Mujib lay on the floor, dead ... A group searched the ground floor. In the lavatories, they found Sheikh Nasser and a couple of servants and gunned them down. The other group charged into Mujib's bedroom. There they found the two daughters-in-law of Mujib along with Sheikh Jamal and Sheikh Russel ... they, too, were not spared by these butchers.\"</ref> \n\nIn [[Dhanmondi]], two other groups of soldiers killed [[Sheikh Fazlul Haque Mani]], Mujib's nephew and a leader of the Awami League along with his pregnant wife, Arzu Moni, and [[Abdur Rab Serniabat]], Mujib's brother-in-law. They also killed a minister of the government and thirteen of his family members on Mintu Road.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|p=65}}: \"Lieutenant Moalemuddin sped for the residence of Sheikh Mani with three trucks full of soldiers ... while Major Shahriar and Captain Huda went out with some soldiers to get rid of Minister Abdur Rab Sarniabat.\"</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 3}}: \"At the same time at 13/1 Dhanmandi Sheikh Fazlul Haq and his pregnant wife, and on Mineta Road, Abdur Rab Sarniabat with the 13 members of his family, were butchered ...\"</ref>\n\nThe fourth and most powerful group was sent towards Savar to repel the expected counter-attack by the security forces stationed there. After a brief fight and the loss of eleven men, the security forces surrendered.<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978||loc=p. 64, para 1}}: \"[The] fourth group, the most powerful of the lot, proceeded towards Savar, near Dacca, to repel the anticipated counter-attack by the Security Forces. It did run against some resistance at Savar. But once the shelling took toll of eleven people, the leaderless Security Force surrendered\"</ref>\n\nFour of the founding leaders of the Awami League, first Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Tajuddin Ahmed]], former Prime Minister [[Mansur Ali]], former Vice President [[Syed Nazrul Islam]], and former Home Minister [[A.&nbsp;H.&nbsp;M. Qamaruzzaman]], were arrested. Three months later, on 3 November 1975, they [[Jail Killing Day|were murdered]] in [[Dhaka Central Jail]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dasgupta|1978|pp=77\u201378}}: \"3 November ... Khondakar also knew that the situation was bound to be grave once Nazrul Islam, Tajuddin Ahmed, Kamaruzzaman and Mansur Ali were released ... Khondakar had had them arrested under various pretexts shortly after Mujib's assassination, and they were still rotting in Dacca Jail. So, Khondakar ... managed to allow the associates of the \"killers\" [the seven Majors who assassinated Sheikh Mujibur Rahman] inside the jail to brutally kill these four leaders.\"</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of assassination===\n[[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]] assumed the presidency, and [[Major General]] [[Ziaur Rahman]] became the new Chief of Army Staff. The leading conspirators were all given high government ranks. They were all later toppled by yet another coup led by [[Brigadier General]] [[Khaled Mosharraf]] on 3 November 1975. Mosharraf himself was killed during a counter-revolt four days later on 7 November, which freed Major General Ziaur Rahman in power and was brought in to bring law and order. \n\nMajor [[Syed Faruque Rahman]], Rashid, and the other army officers were promoted to the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]]. Nevertheless, they were exiled to [[Libyan Arab Republic|Libya]], China, [[Rhodesia]], Canada, and other countries, although they were given several diplomatic posts in Bangladeshi missions abroad. Lieutenant Colonel (Rtd.) Syed Faruque Rahman later returned and founded the [[Bangladesh Freedom Party]] in 1985 and took part in the presidential election in 1987 against the military ruler [[Lieutenant General]] [[Hussain Mohammad Ershad]] but lost that election in a landslide.\n\nMujib's two daughters, [[Sheikh Hasina]] and [[Sheikh Rehana]], were in [[West Germany]] at the time of his assassination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladeshi PM Sheikh Hasina requests extradition of Bangabandhu killers from US |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/international/bangladeshi-pm-sheikh-hasina-requests-extradition-of-bangabandhu-killers-from-us-116083000733_1.html |newspaper=Business Standard |agency=Press Trust of India |date=30 August 2016 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> After the coup, they flew back to India, instead of Bangladesh and took refuge with the Indian government. Sheikh Hasina lived in New Delhi in a self-imposed exile before returning to Bangladesh on 17 May 1981.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ahmed |first=Helal Uddin |year=2012 |chapter=Hasina, Sheikh |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Hasina,_Sheikh |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>\n\n===Trial===\nThe military decided not to [[court-martial]] the military officers who masterminded and participated in the coup. [[AFM Mohitul Islam|A.&nbsp;F.&nbsp;M. Mohitul Islam]], personal assistant to Sheikh Mujib and a survivor of the attack on his house, attempted to file a case against the military officers, but the police slapped him in the face and refused to file the report.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ordeals of plaintiff |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/august-15-special-coverage/ordeals-plaintiff-1269652 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009 |access-date=2 January 2017}}</ref> The assassination conspirators could not be tried in a court of law because of the [[Indemnity Act, Bangladesh|Indemnity Act]] passed by the government under President [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad]]. When the Awami League, led by Mujib's daughter [[Sheikh Hasina]], won elections in 1996, the act was repealed. The Bangabandhu murder trial began with the case filing by A.&nbsp;F.&nbsp;M. Mohitul Islam.<ref name=\"hfxb\">{{cite news |title=Mohitul Islam passes away |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/mohitul-islam-passes-away-1275547 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=26 August 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nColonel (Rtd.) [[Syed Faruque Rahman]] was arrested from his Dhaka home, and Colonel (Rtd.) [[Bazlul Huda]] was brought back from [[Bangkok]], where he was serving a prison sentence for [[shop lifting|shoplifting]] as part of a criminal exchange program between [[Thailand]] and Bangladesh. Lieutenant Colonel [[Mohiuddin Ahmed]] was in active military service when he was arrested. Colonel (Rtd.) [[Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan]] had been appointed to active diplomatic service by previous Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Begum Khaleda Zia]], but he returned to Bangladesh and was arrested when he was recalled by the foreign ministry. Colonel (Rtd.) [[Abdur Rashid]] and other accused individuals had already left Bangladesh, however. They believed that the upcoming 1996 general election would be an Awami League victory, which would result in the repealing of the Indemnity Act and their subsequent arrest. Colonel (Rtd.) Rashid now reportedly shuttles between Pakistan and Libya. All these men were also involved in [[Jail Killing Day]] on 3 November 1975, when four Awami League officials were assassinated.{{citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\nThe first trial ended on 8 November 1998. The District and Session Judge of Dhaka, Mohammad Golam Rasul, ordered the death sentence by firing squad to fifteen out of the twenty accused of conspiring in the assassination. The sentences were not carried out immediately, because five of the convicts sought to file appeals in the high court division of the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]]. The Supreme Court, consisting of Justice Mohammad Ruhul Amin and Justice A.&nbsp;B.&nbsp;M. Khairul Haque, who was the former [[Chief Justice of Bangladesh]], gave a divisive verdict. Senior Justice Amin acquitted five out of the original fifteen accused, whereas Junior Justice Haque upheld the lower court's verdict. A verdict from a third judge became necessary. Later, Justice Mohammad Fazlul Karim condemned twelve out of original fifteen, including two acquitted in Justice Amin's verdict. \n\nOne of the convicts, Major (Rtd.) Aziz Pasha died in Zimbabwe on 2 June 2001.<ref>[http://www.peoplesmouth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7220:6-killers-still-out-of-reach&catid=34:jv-slideshow 6 killers still out of reach]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221162331/http://www.peoplesmouth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7220%3A6-killers-still-out-of-reach&catid=34%3Ajv-slideshow |date=21 February 2014 }}</ref> Although the five accused appealed to the [[Law of Bangladesh#The Appellate Division|appellate division of the Supreme Court]], their decision remained pending from August 2001. Several judges refused to hear the case, which meant the government lacked the three judges required to hold a hearing session. On 18 June 2007, one of the conspirators who had been sentenced to death, Major (Rtd.) A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed was extradited to Bangladesh from the United States following a series of failed attempts to gain [[right of asylum|asylum]] or [[permanent residency]] in the United States. On 7 August 2007, the murder case hearings resumed after a six year delay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangabandhu murder case hearing resumes today after 6 years |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/08/07/d7080701033.htm |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=7 August 2007}}</ref> The appellate division of the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]] gave its verdict on 19 November 2009,<ref>''Major Md. Bazlul Huda (Artillery) & Ors. vs. The State'', [http://www.supremecourt.gov.bd/scweb/documents/325397_judgements1.pdf Criminal Appeal Nos. 55\u201359 of 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922200140/http://www.supremecourt.gov.bd/scweb/documents/325397_judgements1.pdf |date=22 September 2013 }}</ref> after a five-member special bench, headed by Justice Mahammad Tafazzal Islam, spent 29 days hearing the petition filed by the convicted.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite news |title=Mujib murder case appeals verdict today |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802230939/http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |archive-date=2 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Security tightened around SC |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=114637 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=19 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe appeal of the convicts was rejected, and the death sentence was upheld.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title=Bangladesh officers lose appeal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8366329.stm |work=BBC News |date=19 November 2009}}</ref> Before the verdict, approximately 12,000 extra policemen were deployed to guard strategic buildings, including the Supreme Court building, to prevent disruption of the proceedings by the convicted men's supporters.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Nevertheless, they were blamed by the government for a grenade attack on one of the prosecution lawyers in October 2009, although no one has been charged yet.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nCaptain (Rtd.) [[Qismet Hashem]], Captain (Rtd.) [[Nazmul Hossain Aanssar]], and Major (Rtd.) [[Abdul Majid (officer)|Abdul Majid]] were acquitted through the high court division and appellate division verdicts and now live in Canada. [[Taheruddin Thakur]], former Information Minister and one of the suspects, was cleared during the Hasina Government, acquitted in trial, and released. He died naturally in 2009.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite news |title=Mujib murder case appeals verdict today |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802230939/http://www.newagebd.com/2009/nov/19/front.html#2 |archive-date=2 August 2010}}</ref> Conspirators Major (Rtd.) Bazlul Huda, Lieutenant Colonel (Rtd.) Mohiuddin Ahmed, Major (Rtd.) [[A.K.M. Mohiuddin Ahmed|A.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;M. Mohiuddin Ahmed]], Colonel (Rtd.) [[Syed Faruque Rahman]], and Colonel (Rtd.) Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan was executed on 28 January 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ahmed |first=Anis |date=27 January 2010 |title=Bangladesh Hangs Killers of Independence Leader Mujib |newspaper=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE60Q67320100127}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |author=Charlie Gillis |date=15 February 2011 |title=The assassin among us \u2013 Nur Chowdhury faces execution for killing Bangladesh's president. That's why he's safe in Canada. |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/02/15/the-assassin-among-us-2/ |magazine=[[Maclean's]]}}</ref>\nOn April 11 2020 Abdul Masjed was executed by hanging. He had returned to Bangladesh the previous month after being a fugitive for 23 years.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52258557</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[BAKSAL]]\n* [[15 August 1975 Bangladesh coup d'\u00e9tat]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Dasgupta |first=Sukharanjan |title=Midnight Massacre in Dacca |year=1978 |location=New Delhi |publisher=Vikas |isbn=0-7069-0692-6 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Coord|23.7517|N|90.3767|E|region:BD_type:event|display=title}}\n{{Sheikh Mujibur Rahman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rahman}}\n[[Category:1975 crimes in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:1975 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:1975 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:1970s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1970s mass shootings in Asia]]\n[[Category:1990s trials]]\n[[Category:20th century in Dhaka]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman| ]]\n[[Category:August 1975 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1975 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1975]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Bangladesh]]\n<!--[[Category:Mass shootings in Bangladesh]]-->\n[[Category:Military coups in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Murder in Dhaka]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n[[Category:Trials in Bangladesh]]\n", "name_user": "DiplomatTesterMan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrial:mos date ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assassination_of_Sheikh_Mujibur_Rahman"}
{"title_page": "2016 Michigan Wolverines football team", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n |year=2016\n |team=Michigan Wolverines\n |image = Michigan Wolverines logo.svg\n |image_size = 150px\n |conference=Big Ten Conference\n |division=East Division\n |short_conf=Big Ten\n |record= 10\u20133\n |conf_record= 7\u20132\n |CoachRank= 10\n |APRank= 10\n |CFPRank= \n |head_coach= [[Jim Harbaugh]]\n |hc_year= 2nd \n |off_coach= [[Tim Drevno]]\n |oc_year= 2nd\n |def_coach=[[Don Brown (American football coach)|Don Brown]] \n |dc_year=1st \n |off_scheme= [[Pro-style offense|Pro-style]]\n |def_scheme=[[4\u20133 defense|4\u20133]]\n |mvp=[[Jabrill Peppers]]\n |captain=[[Jake Butt]]\n |captain_year= Senior\n |captain2= [[Chris Wormley]]\n |captain2_year=Senior\n |stadium=[[Michigan Stadium]]<br />(Capacity: 107,601)\n |uniform=Michigan wolverines football uniforms.png\n |bowl= [[2016 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n |bowl_result = L 32\u201333 vs. [[2016 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]]\n}}\n{{2016 Big Ten football standings}}\n\nThe '''2016 Michigan Wolverines football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented the [[University of Michigan]] during the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Wolverines played in the East Division of the [[Big Ten Conference]] and played their home games at [[Michigan Stadium]] in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]. Michigan was led by head coach [[Jim Harbaugh]], who was in his second season.\n\nComing off the team's first 10-win season in four years in Jim Harbaugh's first season as head coach in [[2015 Michigan Wolverines football team|2015]], Michigan began the year with high expectations, being ranked seventh in the preseason [[AP Poll]]. They won their three non-conference games in dominant fashion. In the following two games, the Wolverines obtained consecutive top-10 victories over [[2016 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] and [[2016 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], the two teams who would end up playing in the Big Ten Championship game. Michigan continued to win, rising to number two in the [[College Football Playoff]] rankings at 9\u20130 before falling on the road to [[2016 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|Iowa]] on a last-second field goal. Two weeks later, Michigan traveled to [[Columbus, Ohio]] to face arch-rival [[2016 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] with an opportunity to claim a spot in the [[2016 Big Ten Football Championship Game]] with a win. The Wolverines lost in double overtime, 27\u201330, ending the regular season in third in the Eastern Division behind Ohio State and Penn State. Michigan received an invitation to the [[2016 Orange Bowl]], where they lost to [[2016 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]], 32\u201333 to end the year at 10\u20133.\n\nThe team was led by [[2016 College Football All-America Team|unanimous first-team All-American]] linebacker [[Jabrill Peppers]], who was the [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year|Big Ten Defensive Player of the Year]] and a finalist for the [[Heisman Trophy]], finishing in fifth. Cornerback [[Jourdan Lewis]] was also a consensus first-team All-American, as was tight end [[Jake Butt]], who was the recipient of the [[John Mackey Award]] as the nation's top tight end. Quarterback [[Wilton Speight]] led the team in passing, finishing with 2,538 yards and 18 touchdowns on the year.\n\n==Preseason==\nIn [[2015 Michigan Wolverines football team|2015]], Michigan compiled a 10\u20133 record (6\u20132 in conference play) during the regular season and played the [[2015 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]] in the [[2016 Citrus Bowl (January)|Citrus Bowl]], where Michigan defeated the Gators 41\u20137. This was Michigan's best record since the [[2011 Michigan Wolverines football team|2011 season]], which saw Michigan finish with an 11\u20132 record and a [[2012 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl victory]] over [[2011 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]].\n\nMichigan suffered staff attrition when [[defensive coordinator]] [[D. J. Durkin]] left the program to become the head coach at [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2015/12/report_michigan_dc_dj_durkin_h.html#incart_2box_news_ann-arbor|title=Report: Michigan DC D.J. Durkin hired as Maryland's head coach|accessdate=December 2, 2015|date=December 2, 2015|publisher=[[MLive]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> On December 21, 2015, Michigan officially announced the hiring of [[Don Brown (American football coach)|Don Brown]] as defensive coordinator.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harbaugh Hires Brown to Coordinate U-M Defense|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/122115aaa.html|work=MGoBlue.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=December 21, 2015|date=December 21, 2015}}</ref> On January 7, 2016, it was officially announced that John Baxter would be leaving Michigan to become the Special Teams coach at [[USC Trojans football|USC]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=John Baxter Returns To USC As Special Teams Coordinator|url=http://www.usctrojans.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010716aaa.html|website=USCTrojans.com|accessdate=January 15, 2016}}</ref> In response to both the Baxter and Durkin departures\u2014Durkin had also coached linebackers for Michigan in addition to his position as defensive coordinator\u2014Michigan promoted their recruiting coordinator Chris Partridge to Special Teams and Linebackers coach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partridge Announced as Linebackers and Special Teams Coach|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011416aad.html|website=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=January 15, 2016|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, [[Greg Jackson (American football)|Greg Jackson]] left Michigan to become the defensive backs coach of the [[Dallas Cowboys]]. He was replaced by Brian Smith, who most recently served as an assistant linebackers coach with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] under [[Chip Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brian Smith Named Michigan's Defensive Backs Coach|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/030416aaa.html|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20160829 Michigan Wolverines and Jumpman logo at Nike Flagship store before opening weekend.jpg|left|thumb|[[Michigan Wolverines]] logo and the [[Jumpman (logo)|jumpman logo]] at the [[Nike, Inc.]] flagship store on the [[Magnificent Mile]] during the week before the opening game]]\n\nThe team conducted four of its spring practices at the [[IMG Academy]] in [[Bradenton, Florida]] between February 29 and March 4, 2016, which coincided with the University's annual [[spring break]]. The final practice was held as an open practice for fans and recruits,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/02/michigan_will_have_an_open_pra.html#incart_most-commented_wolverines_article|title=Michigan will have an open practice (March 4) at IMG Academy in Bradenton, Florida|accessdate=February 25, 2016|date=February 24, 2016|website=[[MLive.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> and saw an attendance of over 5,000 people. The practices were considered controversial, as coaches from the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] and [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] protested what they believed to be an attempt to gain an upper hand in recruiting prospective athletes; however, at the time, no NCAA rules stated that the practices would not be allowed to take place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2016/03/05/jim-harbaugh-michigan-wolverines-football-practice-img-academy-bradenton-florida-sec/81350664/|title=Jim Harbaugh, Michigan create buzz, challenge convention with Florida 'circus'|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=March 5, 2016|website=USAToday.com|publisher=[[USA Today]]|author=Wolken, Dan}}</ref> Michigan also conducted several satellite camps\u2014football camps meant to expose prospective student athletes to colleges who might otherwise not find and recruit them due to distance or other factors\u2014in 22 states, [[Australia]], and [[American Samoa]] following the NCAA's reversal of a ban enacted only months prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/inside-michigan-coach-jim-harbaughs-infamous-satellite-camps/|title=Inside Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh's infamous satellite camps|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=June 7, 2016|website=CBSSports.com|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Solomon, Jon}}</ref>\n\nAlthough agreed to many months earlier,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/16/sports/michigans-nike-deal-among-richest-in-college-sports.html|title=Michigan\u2019s Nike Deal Among Richest in College Sports|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=July 15, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Tracy, Marc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/07/15/news/michigan-nike-deal/|title=Nike lands $169 million deal with Michigan|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=July 15, 2016|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=Wattles, Jackie}}</ref> in April, the University announced it had signed an 11-year, $127.12 million contract with [[Nike, Inc.]] on March 16 that would go into effect on August 1, 2016 for 31 [[Michigan Wolverines]] sports teams to switch from wearing [[Adidas]] apparel to Nike.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/04/26/michigan-nike-contract/83533954/|title=Michigan finalizes Nike contract for up to $173.8 million|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=April 26, 2016|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref> The Wolverines became the first football program to wear the [[jumpman (logo)|jumpman logo]] and every piece of football apparel donned by the team that is visible is [[Jordan Brand]] attire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/07/25/michigan-players-psyched-don-jordan-jumpman-uniforms/87550954/|title=Michigan players psyched to don Jordan Jumpman uniforms|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=July 26, 2016|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Chengelis, Angelique S.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/08/michigan_players_show_off_new.html|title=Michigan players show off new Jumpman cleats, Jordan Brand gear|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=August 1, 2016|publisher=[[MLive.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Michigan unveiled its new uniforms and gear during a ceremony at the [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] [[Piquette Avenue Industrial Historic District|Piquette Avenue Plant]] on August 2. Michigan alumna [[Dana Jacobson]] hosted the event, while former Wolverine great [[Charles Woodson]] was also in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.michigandaily.com/section/football/harbaugh-michigan-unveil-new-football-jerseys|title=Harbaugh, Michigan unveil new football jerseys|accessdate=September 15, 2016|date=August 2, 2016|publisher=[[Michigan Daily]]|author=Sang, Orion}}</ref>\n\n==Recruiting==\n\n===Position key===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[Running back|Back]]\n|'''B'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Center (American football)|Center]]\n|'''C'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Cornerback]]\n|'''CB'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Defensive back]]\n|'''DB'''\n|-\n|[[Defensive end]]\n|'''DE'''\n|[[Defensive lineman]]\n|'''DL'''\n|[[Defensive tackle]]\n|'''DT'''\n|[[End (American football)|End]]\n|'''E'''\n|-\n|[[Fullback (American football)|Fullback]]\n|'''FB'''\n|[[Guard (American football)|Guard]]\n|'''G'''\n|[[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]]\n|'''HB'''\n|[[Placekicker|Kicker]]\n|'''K'''\n|-\n|[[Kickoff returner]]\n|'''KR'''\n|[[Offensive tackle]]\n|'''OT'''\n|[[Lineman (American football)|Offensive lineman]]\n|'''OL'''\n|[[Linebacker]]\n|'''LB'''\n|-\n|[[Long snapper]]\n|'''LS'''\n|[[Punter (American football)|Punter]]\n|'''P'''\n|[[Punt returner]]\n|'''PR'''\n|[[Quarterback]]\n|'''QB'''\n|-\n|[[Running back]]\n|'''RB'''\n|[[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|Safety]]\n|'''S'''\n|[[Tight end]]\n|'''TE'''\n|[[Wide receiver]]\n|'''WR'''\n|}\n\n===Recruits===\n\nMichigan's [[Recruiting (college athletics)|recruiting class]] consisted of 28 recruits, including seven that enrolled early. Michigan's recruiting class was ranked No. 6 by [[Scout.com|Scout]], No. 4 by [[Rivals.com|Rivals]], and No. 6 by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://michigan.scout.com/a.z?s=162&p=9&c=14&yr=2016|title=2016 Team Rankings|accessdate=February 3, 2016|publisher=Scout|work=Scout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/teamrank/2016/all/all|title=2016 Team Rankings|accessdate=February 3, 2016|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|work=Rivals.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/classrankings?classyear=2016|title=2016 Team Rankings|accessdate=February 3, 2016|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> The highlight of the class was the consensus number one recruit in the country, [[Rashan Gary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2015/01/greg_mattison_keeps_bond_with.html|title=Rashan Gary, nation's No. 1-ranked recruit, commits to Michigan|accessdate=February 3, 2016|date=February 3, 2016|publisher=[[MLive]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U-M Lands Top-Five National Recruiting Class with 28 Signees|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=February 3, 2016|date=February 3, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020316aaa.html}}</ref>\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2016}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit = [[Devin Asiasi]]\n| position = TE\n| hometown