. 5 in the AP Poll and No. 6 in the Coaches' Poll,<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 2|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/2|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 6, 2016}}</ref> and then rose to No. 4 in the AP Poll and No. 5 in the Coaches' Poll following its victory over UCF.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 3|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/3|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> Michigan held serve in the polls following its victories over Colorado<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 4|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/4|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 25, 2016}}</ref> and Penn State.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 5|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/5|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 25, 2016}}</ref> Michigan rose to No. 4 in the Coaches' Poll following its victory over Wisconsin,<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 6|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/6|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 10, 2016}}</ref> and remained at No. 4 in both polls following its win over Rutgers.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 7|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/7|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 10, 2016}}</ref> Michigan rose to No. 3 in the AP Poll during its bye week.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 8|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/8|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 10, 2016}}</ref> Michigan rose to No. 2 in both polls following its victory over Michigan State and was ranked No. 3 in the season's first edition of the College Football Playoff (CFP) rankings.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 9|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/9|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> Following its loss to Iowa, Michigan fell to No. 4 in both polls, but remained at No. 3 in the CFP rankings.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 12|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/12|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> Michigan rose to No. 3 in the AP Poll following its victory over Indiana, and remained at No. 4 in the Coaches' Poll, and No. 3 in the CFP rankings.<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Week 12|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/rankings/_/seasontype/2/year/2016/week/13|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref>\n{{NCAA Division I FBS CFP ranking movements\n| year = {{2016}}\n| finalpollweek = 15\n| cfpfirstweek = 9\n| AP_pre = 7 <small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_pre = 8\n| AP_1 = 5 <small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_1 = 6\n| AP_2 = 4 <small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_2 = 5\n| AP_3 = 4<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_3 = 5\n| AP_4 = 4<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_4 = 5\n| AP_5 = 4<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_5 = 4\n| AP_6 = 4<small> (1) </small> \n| coaches_6  = 4 \n| AP_7 = 3<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_7 = 4\n| AP_8 = 2<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_8 = 2\n| AP_9 = 2<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_9 = 2\n| cfp_9 =3\n| AP_10 = 2<small> (1) </small>\n| coaches_10 = 3\n| cfp_10 = 3\n| AP_11 = 4\n| coaches_11 = 4\n| cfp_11 = 3\n| AP_12 = 3\n| coaches_12 = 4\n| cfp_12 = 3\n| AP_13 = 5\n| coaches_13 = 6\n| cfp_13 = 5\n| AP_14 = 6\n| coaches_14 = 6\n| cfp_14 = 6\n| AP_15 = 10\n| coaches_15 = 10\n}}\n\n==Radio==\nRadio coverage for all games was broadcast statewide on The [[Michigan IMG Sports Network]] and on [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]. The radio announcers are [[Jim Brandstatter]] with [[play-by-play]], [[Dan Dierdorf]] with [[color commentary]], and [[Doug Karsch]] with [[sideline reporter|sideline reports]].<ref name=schedule>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fbl-broadcast.html|title=2016 Michigan Football Broadcast Information|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 3, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101033449/http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fbl-broadcast.html|archivedate=January 1, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Game summaries==\n\n===vs. Hawaii===\n{{see also|2016 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Hawaii at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = Rainbow Warriors\n| Host = '''#7 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 3\n| H1 = 14 | H2 = 21 | H3 = 21 | H4 = 7\n| Date = September 3\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 12:01 PM\n| ElapsedTime = 3:17\n| Attendance = 110,222\n| Weather = Mid 70s, Sunny and clear, W 10\u201315 MPH\n| Referee = Jerry McGinn\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Mike Patrick]], [[Ed Cunningham]] & [[Jerry Punch]]\n|TVStation=ESPN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Hawaii /><ref>{{cite news|title=Hawaii\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=August 30, 2016|date=August 29, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20160829aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=7:29|Team=MICH|Event=Grant Perry 12-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=1:25|Team=MICH|Event=Jake Butt 19-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=11:21|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 5-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=10:36|Team=MICH|Event=Lano Hill 27-yard interception return (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 28\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=6:07|Team=MICH|Event=Chris Evans 18-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 35\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=13:44|Team=MICH|Event=Chris Evans 43-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 42\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=10:51|Team=MICH|Event=[[Channing Stribling]] 51-yard interception return (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 49\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=:18|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 4-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 56\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=12:30|Team=UH|Event=[[Rigoberto Sanchez]] 55-yard field goal|Score=MICH 56\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=7:15|Team=MICH|Event=[[Karan Higdon]] 5-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 63\u20133|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 2\u20130\n| November 28, 1998\n| Michigan, 48\u201317\n|}\n\nTo begin the season, Michigan hosted the Hawaii Rainbow Warriors. This was the first meeting between the teams since 1998, which saw Michigan defeat Hawaii 48\u201317.<ref name=HNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #7 Michigan 63, Hawaii 3|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 3, 2016|date=September 3, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090316aaf.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won in a [[Blowout (sports)|blowout]], 63\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Earns 60-Point Victory over Hawaii to Begin 2016|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 3, 2016|date=September 3, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090316aab.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a 12-yard [[touchdown]] pass from [[Wilton Speight]] to Grant Perry and added to its lead with a 19-yard touchdown pass from Speight to [[Jake Butt]]. Michigan added 21 points in the second quarter via a five-yard touchdown pass from Speight to [[Amara Darboh]], a [[Lano Hill]] 27-yard [[interception]] return for a touchdown (pick six), and an 18-yard touchdown run from freshman running back [[Chris Evans (American football)|Chris Evans]], which made the score 35\u20130 in favor of Michigan at [[half-time]]. Michigan extended its lead early in the third quarter with a 43-yard touchdown run from Evans, and then added fourteen more points via a Channing Stribling 51-yard interception return for a touchdown and a four-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill. Hawaii reduced Michigan's lead to 53 with a 55-yard [[field goal]] from Rigoberto Sanchez, but Michigan ended the scoring with a five-yard touchdown run from Karan Higdon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hawaii-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 3, 2016|date=September 3, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869180}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's honorary captain for the game was [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] Hall of Famer [[Michael Jordan]], while former Wolverines [[Charles Woodson]] and [[Lamarr Woodley]] were also honored during the game. Michigan's 60-point margin of victory was the seventh highest margin of victory in program history and the highest since Michigan defeated [[1975 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]] 69\u20130 in [[1975 Michigan Wolverines football team|1975]]. The game marked the fourth time in program history that Michigan did not punt during a game, and the first time since [[2009 Michigan Wolverines football team|2009]] (against [[Delaware State Hornets football|Delaware State]]). This was the first time Michigan had two pick sixes in a game since the [[1999 Citrus Bowl]] against [[1998 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] and the first time since [[2011 Michigan Wolverines football team|2011]] that it had two defensive touchdowns in one game. Thirty-three Wolverines made their collegiate debut, while seventeen true freshmen appeared in the game, setting a program record.<ref name=HNotes/> Evans\u2014appearing in his first college game\u2014rushed for 112 yards and two touchdowns on eight carries. He became just the third Wolverine true freshman to surpass 100 rushing yards in his collegiate debut, joining Walter Cross (104 yards, September 12, 1998) and [[Chris Perry (American football)|Chris Perry]] (103 yards, September 2, 2000).<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan-Hawaii observations: Speight settles in, Chris Evans a home-run hitter|newspaper=Mlive.com|author=Baumgardner, Nick|date=September 3, 2016|accessdate=September 3, 2016|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/09/michigan-hawaii_observations_s.html}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. UCF===\n{{see also|2016 UCF Knights football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''UCF at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = Knights\n| Host = '''#5 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 0 \n| H1 = 21 | H2 = 13 | H3 = 10 | H4 = 7\n| Date = September 10\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 12:06 PM\n| ElapsedTime = 3:27\n| Attendance = 109,295\n| Weather = Mid 70s, Cloudy with rain, SW 15\u201325 MPH\n| Referee = John O'Neill\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Steve Levy]], [[Brian Griese]] & [[Todd McShay]]\n|TVStation=ABC\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=UCF/><ref>{{cite news|title=UCF\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 5, 2016|date=September 5, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20160905aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=8:48|Team=MICH|Event=Jake Butt 3-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=3:29|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 2-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=1:55|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 45-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=14:17|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 24-yard field goal|Score=MICH 24\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=11:30|Team=MICH|Event=Jake Butt 14-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 31\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=11:10|Team=UCF|Event=Adrian Killins 87-yard run (Matthew Wright kick)|Score=MICH 31\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=6:07|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 36-yard field goal|Score=MICH 34\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=11:47|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 41\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=9:44|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 37-yard field goal|Score=MICH 44\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=11:10|Team=UCF|Event=Dontravious Wilson 34-yard run (Matthew Wright kick)|Score=MICH 44\u201314}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=10:24|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 30-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 51\u201314|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|- align=\"center\"\n| colspan=3| ''First meeting''\n|}\n\nFollowing its opening game against Hawaii, Michigan hosted the Central Florida (UCF) Knights. This was the first ever meeting between the two teams.<ref name=UCFNotes >{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #5 Michigan 51, Central Florida 14|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 10, 2016|date=September 10, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091016aad.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won in another lopsided victory, 51\u201314.<ref>{{cite news|title=Passing Game, Special Teams Lead Wolverines Past UCF|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 10, 2016|date=September 10, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091016aaa.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a three-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Butt, and added to its lead via a two-yard touchdown run from Hill and a 45-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Darboh. Michigan added 13 points in the second quarter via a 24-yard, and 36-yard field goal from Allen, and a 14-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Butt. UCF reduced Michigan's lead to 27 points via an 87-yard touchdown run from Adrian Killins, which made the score 34\u20137 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Michigan extended its lead in the third quarter via a one-yard touchdown run from Hill and a 37-yard field goal by Allen. UCF reduced Michigan's lead to 30 points via a 34-yard touchdown run from Dontravious Wilson. Michigan ended the scoring in the fourth quarter with a 30-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Darboh.<ref>{{cite web|title=UCF-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 10, 2016|date=September 10, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869510}}</ref>\n\nMichigan posted back-to-back 50-plus-point performances for the first time since [[1992 Michigan Wolverines football team|1992]]. Michigan combined for 114 total points in its first two games of the season, the most in program history in more than 100 years.<ref name=UCFNotes/><ref>The [[1892 Michigan Wolverines football team|1892 team]] scored 142 points in its first two games; the [[1902 Michigan Wolverines football team|1902 \"Point-a-Minute\" team]] scored 136 points; and the [[1914 Michigan Wolverines football team|1914 team]] scored 127 points).</ref> Over his first two games, Speight has seven touchdown passes, tying him with [[John Navarre]] for the most touchdown passes in the first two games of a season by a Michigan quarterback. Butt had seven receptions with two touchdowns for the first multi-touchdown game of his career. Butt's seven receptions give him 100 for his career, moving him into third place for career receptions by a tight end.<ref name=UCFNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Colorado===\n{{see also|2016 Colorado Buffaloes football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Colorado at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = Buffaloes\n| Host = '''#4 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 21 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 0\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 17 | H3 = 14 | H4 = 7\n| Date = September 17\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 3:42 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:22\n| Attendance = 110,042\n| Weather = Mid 70s, Cloudy with possible rain, SW 10\u201315 MPH\n| Referee =Mike Cannon\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Kevin Kugler]], [[Matt Millen]] & [[Lisa Byington]]\n|TVStation=BTN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Colorado /><ref>{{cite news|title=UCF\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 5, 2016|date=September 5, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20160905aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=12:37|Team=COLO|Event=Devin Ross 37-yard pass from [[Sefo Liufau]] (Diego Gonzalez kick)|Score=COLO 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=11:48|Team=COLO|Event=Dere McCartney 18-yard fumble return (Diego Gonzalez kick)|Score=COLO 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=8:27|Team=MICH|Event=Grant Perry 6-yard blocked punt return (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=COLO 14\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=3:49|Team=COLO|Event=Devin Ross 6-yard pass from Sefo Liufau (Diego Gonzalez)|Score=COLO 21\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=8:49|Team=MICH|Event=Jehu Chesson 17-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=COLO 21\u201314}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=1:59|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 39-yard field goal|Score=COLO 21\u201317}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=:33|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 45-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 24\u201321}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=14:02|Team=MICH|Event=[[Shay Fields]] 70-yard pass from Sefo Liufau (Diego Gonzalez kick)|Score=COLO 28\u201324}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=13:16|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 42-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 31\u201328}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=3:06|Team=MICH|Event=Ty Isaac 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 38\u201328}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=11:27|Team=MICH|Event=Jabrill Peppers 54-yard punt return (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 45\u201328|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 3\u20131\n| September 13, 1997\n| Michigan, 27\u20133\n|}\n\nAfter playing UCF, Michigan hosted the Colorado Buffaloes. This was the first meeting between the schools since 1997, which saw Michigan win its opener en route to a national championship.<ref name=ColoradoNotes >{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #4 Michigan 45, Colorado 28|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016|date=September 17, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091716aae.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan overcame a 14-point first quarter deficit and won the game 45\u201328. This was the 14th time that Michigan has overcome a deficit of 14 points or more to win.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big-Play Wolverines Trample Buffaloes in Non-Conference Finale|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 10, 2016|date=September 10, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091716aaa.html}}</ref> Colorado opened the scoring in the first quarter via a 37-yard touchdown pass from Sefo Liufau to Devin Ross and added to its lead via an 18-yard fumble recovery for a touchdown by Dere McCartney. Michigan responded with a six-yard blocked punt touchdown return by Grant Perry, which reduced Colorado's lead to seven points. Colorado regained its 14-point lead via a six-yard touchdown pass from Liufau to Devin Ross. Michigan responded with 17 unanswered points in the second quarter: a 17-yard touchdown run from Jehu Chesson, a 39-yard field goal by [[Kenny Allen (American football)|Kenny Allen]], and a 45-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Darboh, which made the score 24\u201321 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Colorado regained the lead in the third quarter via a 70-yard touchdown pass from Liufau to Shay Fields, but Michigan regained the lead with a  42-yard touchdown run from [[De'Veon Smith]]. Michigan added to its lead with a one-yard touchdown run from [[Ty Isaac]], and then ended the scoring in the fourth quarter with a 54-yard punt return for a touchdown from [[Jabrill Peppers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016|date=September 17, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869111}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's honorary captains for the game were former Michigan and current [[New England Patriots]] quarterback [[Tom Brady]] and [[Activision Blizzard]] CEO [[Robert Kotick]]. Michigan has combined for 159 total points over its first three games of the 2016 season, the most over that stretch in program history. Michigan scored two touchdowns off punts returns in a single game for just the second time in program history, and the first time since [[1954 Michigan Wolverines football team|1954]]. Jake Butt posted seven receptions for 87 yards and moved into third among Michigan's all-time leaders in receiving yards by a tight end with 1,292.<ref name=ColoradoNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Penn State===\n{{see also|2016 Penn State Nittany Lions football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Penn State at Michigan''' \n| Visitor = Nittany Lions\n| Host = '''#4 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 3 | V4 = 7\n| H1 = 14 | H2 = 14 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 14\n| Date = September 24\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br />Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 3:41 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:20\n| Attendance = 110,319\n| Weather = Low 70s, Mostly sunny, N 10\u201315 MPH\n| Referee = Dan Capron\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Dave Flemming]], Brian Griese & Todd McShay\n|TVStation= ABC\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=PSU/><ref>{{cite news|title=Penn State\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=September 19, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20160919aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=9:51|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=3:57|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 2-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=14:09|Team=MICH|Event=Devin Asiasi 3-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=0:46|Team=MICH|Event=Karan Higdon 2-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 28\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=11:31|Team=PSU|Event=Tyler Davis 21-yard field goal|Score=MICH 28\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=2:42|Team=MICH|Event=Chris Evans 3-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 35\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=11:22|Team=PSU|Event=Chris Godwin 8-yard pass from [[Trace McSorley]] (Tyler Davis kick)|Score=MICH 35\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=6:11|Team=MICH|Event=Karan Higdon 40-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 42\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=2:04|Team=MICH|Event=Ty Isaac 3-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 49\u201310|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 12\u20137\n| November 21, 2015\n| Michigan, 28\u201316\n|}\n\nFollowing its game against Colorado, Michigan began its Big Ten portion of the schedule when it hosted the Penn State Nittany Lions. Michigan defeated Penn State 28\u201316 in the previous meeting.<ref name=PSUNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #4 Michigan 49, Penn State 10|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 24, 2016|date=September 24, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091716aae.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won in another blowout, 49\u201310.<ref>{{cite news|title=U-M Rides Six Sacks, Six Rush TDs to Win over PSU in B1G Opener|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 24, 2016|date=September 24, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/092416aaa.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a one-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill, and a two-yard touchdown run from De'Veon Smith. Michigan added to its lead in the second quarter via a three-yard touchdown pass from Wilton Speight to Devin Asiasi, and a two-yard touchdown run from Karan Higdon, which made the score 28\u20130 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Penn State reduced Michigan's lead to 25 with a 21-yard field goal by Tyler Davis in the third quarter. Michigan responded with a three-yard touchdown run from Chris Evans. Penn State opened the scoring in the fourth quarter via an eight-yard pass from Trace McSorley to Chris Godwin. Michigan responded with a 40-yard touchdown run from Karan Higdon, before Ty Isaac added the final points of the game via a three-yard touchdown run.<ref>{{cite web|title=Penn State-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 24, 2016|date=September 24, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869658}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's honorary captain for the game was alumnus Don Graham, the founder of Michigan's Graham Sustainability Institute. Michigan has combined for 208 total points over its first four games of the 2016 season, the most over that stretch in program history. Michigan has scored 40 or more points in each of its first four games for the first time since [[1947 Michigan Wolverines football team|1947]]. Michigan posted a season best six sacks, the most in a game since [[2014 Michigan Wolverines football team|2014]] against [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]].<ref name=PSUNotes/>\n\nWith the win, the Wolverines also retook the all time college football winning percentage from its rival [[Notre Dame football|Notre Dame]].\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Wisconsin===\n{{see also|2016 Wisconsin Badgers football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Wisconsin at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = #8 Badgers\n| Host = '''#4 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 0\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 7\n| Date = October 1\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 3:41 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:21\n| Attendance = 111,846\n| Weather = High 60s, Cloudy possible rain, SE 10\u201315 MPH\n| Referee = Ron Snodgrass\n|TVAnnouncers=Steve Levy, Brian Griese & Todd McShay\n|TVStation=ABC\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Wisconsin/><ref>{{cite news|title=Wisconsin\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=September 26, 2016|date=September 26, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20160926aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=2|Time=14:56|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=8:03|Team=WIS|Event=[[Dare Ogunbowale]] 17-yard pass from [[Alex Hornibrook]] (Andrew Endicott \tkick)|Score=Tie 7\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=7:56|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 46-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20137|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 49\u201314\u20131\n| November 20, 2010\n| Wisconsin, 48\u201328\n|}\n\nAfter facing Penn State, Michigan hosted the Wisconsin Badgers. Despite being in the same conference, these teams had not met since 2010, when Wisconsin defeated Michigan 48\u201328.<ref name=WISNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #4 Michigan 14, #8 Wisconsin 7|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 1, 2016|date=October 1, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/100116aai.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan defeated Wisconsin in a defensive battle, 14\u20137.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverines Win Fourth Quarter, Stay Perfect|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 1, 2016|date=October 1, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/100116aaa.html}}</ref> After neither team scored in the first quarter, Michigan opened the scoring in the second quarter via a one-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill, which made the score 7\u20130 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Wisconsin responded in the third quarter with a 17-yard touchdown pass from Alex Hornibrook to Dare Ogunbowale. Michigan re-gained the lead and ended the scoring in the fourth quarter via a 46-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Darboh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wisconsin-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 1, 2016|date=October 1, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869664}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's honorary captain for the game was former faculty athletics representative, and current University of Michigan English professor Anne Curzan. The win was Michigan's first over a top-10 opponent since beating [[2008 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]] in [[2008 Michigan Wolverines football team|2008]], 27\u201325,<ref name=WISNotes/> ending a streak of 12 consecutive such losses (including two under Harbaugh).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/124540/top-ten-throwdown-how-rare-are-three-top-10-games-in-one-week|title='Top Ten Throwdown:' How rare are three top-10 games in one week?|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=October 4, 2016|date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> Michigan was 0 for 3 on Field Goal attempts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baumgardner|first1=Nick|title=Michigan's 3 missed FGs prompts a 'kicking competition' this week; Quinn Nordin's out|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/10/quinn_nordin_is_out_and_michig.html|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===at Rutgers===\n{{see also|2016 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Michigan at Rutgers'''\n| Visitor = '''#4 Wolverines'''\n| Host = Scarlet Knights\n| V1 = 14 | V2 = 29 | V3 = 14| V4 = 21\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 0 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 0\n| Date = October 8\n| Location = High Point Solutions Stadium <br /> Piscataway, NJ\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 7:10 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:26\n| Attendance = 53,292\n| Weather = 65\u00ba F, Rainy, W 2 MPH\n| Referee = Mike Cannon\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Jason Benetti]], [[Kelly Stouffer]] & Paul Carcaterra\n|TVStation=ESPN2\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Rutgers/><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan\u2013RutgersPre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 3, 2016|date=October 3, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161003aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=7:44|Team=MICH|Event=Ty Isaac 4-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=4:27|Team=MICH|Event=Jehu Chesson 30-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=14:55|Team=MICH|Event=Jabrill Peppers 7-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=11:57|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Garrett Moores rush)|Score=MICH 29\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=7:18|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 36\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=2:10|Team=MICH|Event=Jabrill Peppers 4-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 43\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=10:28|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 11-yard pass from John O'Korn (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 50\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=8:17|Team=MICH|Event=Karan Higdon 15-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 57\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=12:45|Team=MICH|Event=Bobby Henderson 13-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 64\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=9:20|Team=MICH|Event=Karan Higdon 44-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 71\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=7:56|Team=MICH|Event=Ty Isaac 34-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 78\u20130|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 1\u20131\n| November 7, 2015\n| Michigan, 49\u201316\n|}\n\nAfter its game against Wisconsin, Michigan traveled to New Jersey to face Rutgers in Michigan's first road game of the season. Michigan defeated Rutgers 49\u201316 in the previous meeting.<ref name=RutgersNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #4 Michigan 78, Rutgers 0|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 8, 2016|date=October 8, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/100816aaa.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won in a historic blowout, 78\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ground Attack, Defensive Blanket Key U-M's Shutout Win|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 8, 2016|date=October 8, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/100816aac.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a four-yard touchdown run from Ty Isaac. Michigan added to its lead via a 30-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Chesson. Michigan added 29 points in the second quarter via a seven-yard touchdown run from Peppers, two one-yard touchdown runs from Hill, a two-point conversion Garrett Moores rush, and a four-yard touchdown run from Peppers, which made the score 43\u20130 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Michigan added 14 points in the third quarter via an 11-yard touchdown pass from [[John O'Korn]] to Hill, and a 15-yard touchdown run from Karan Higdon. Michigan added 21 points in the fourth quarter via a 13-yard touchdown run from Bobby Henderson, a 44-yard touchdown run from Higdon, and a 34-yard touchdown run from Isaac.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan-Rutgers Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 8, 2016|date=October 8, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869636}}</ref>\n\nThe game was a statistical domination for Michigan. Michigan accumulated 600 yards of offense and eleven touchdowns (nine rushing, two passing); the nine rushing touchdowns tied for the most in modern program history.<ref>Note: Claims that Michigan's nine touchdowns are a program record ignore the accomplishments of [[Fielding H. Yost]]'s \"Point-a-Minute\" teams that scored more than nine touchdowns on multiple occasions. Michigan's single-game record is actually 22 touchdowns, a feat accomplished twice \u2013 on October 26, 1901, against [[Buffalo Bulls football|University of Buffalo]] and on October 24, 1904, against West Virginia. These games occurred before the forward pass was [[Forward pass#1906 rule change|legalized in 1906]]; therefore, all points scored would have been via rushing touchdowns.</ref> Khalid Hill recorded three touchdown scores, making him the first Michigan player with three or more scores since Chesson had four in 2015 against Indiana. Michigan improved to 6\u20130 for the first time since [[2011 Michigan Wolverines football team|2011]] and recorded its first shutout since the previous season against [[2015 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]]. Michigan's defense held Rutgers to only 39 total yards, two first downs, 14 three-and-outs and 0-for-17 on third down. Michigan recorded its largest margin of victory\u2014during either conference or non-conference play\u2014since it defeated [[Chicago Maroons football|Chicago]] 85\u20130 in [[1939 Michigan Wolverines football team|1939]]. This was also the largest margin of victory in any Big Ten game since the same Michigan victory over Chicago.<ref name=RutgersNotes/> The defeat was Rutgers' worst loss since an 82\u20130 loss to [[Princeton Tigers football|Princeton]] in [[1888 Princeton Tigers football team|1888]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stunning stats from Michigan's 78\u20130 destruction of Rutgers|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|work=FoxSports.com|accessdate=October 11, 2016|date=October 8, 2016|author=Werner, Barry|url=http://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/stunning-stats-from-michigans-78-0-destruction-of-rutgers-100816}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Illinois===\n{{see also|2016 Illinois Fighting Illini football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Illinois at Michigan''' <br /> ([[Homecoming|Homecoming game]])\n| Visitor = Fighting Illini\n| Host = '''#3 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 8\n| H1 = 21 | H2 = 10 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 7\n| Date = October 22\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 3:36 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:11\n| Attendance = 111,103\n| Weather = Low 50s, Partly cloudy, NW 20\u201330 MPH\n| Referee = Ron Snodgrass\n|TVAnnouncers=Kevin Kugler, Matt Millen & Lisa Byington\n|TVStation=BTN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Illinois/><ref>{{cite news|title=Illinois\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 18, 2016|date=October 17, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161017aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=10:23|Team=MICH|Event=Jake Butt 3-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=7:52|Team=MICH|Event=Tyrone Wheatley 21-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=1:01|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=11:00|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 4-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 28\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=0:00|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 23-yard field goal|Score=MICH 31\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=0:43|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 27-yard field goal|Score=MICH 34\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=10:22|Team=ILL|Event=Malik Turner 43-yard pass from Jeff George, Jr. (Zach Grant pass from Jeff George, Jr.)|Score=MICH 34\u20138}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=8:48|Team=MICH|Event=Karan Higdon 45-yard run (Ryan Tice kick)|Score=MICH 41\u20138|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 69\u201323\u20132\n| October 13, 2012\n| Michigan, 45\u20130\n|}\n\nFollowing its clash with Rutgers and its [[bye (sports)|bye week]], Michigan hosted the Illinois Fighting Illini for its homecoming game. This was the first meeting between the schools since [[2012 Michigan Wolverines football team|2012]], which saw Michigan defeat Illinois 45\u20130.<ref name=IllinoisNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #3 Michigan 41, Illinois 8|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 22, 2016|date=October 22, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/102216aag.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won the game, 41\u20138.<ref>{{cite news|title=Balanced Offensive Attack Propels U-M Past Illinois on Homecoming|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 22, 2016|date=October 22, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/102216aaa.html}}</ref> Michigan scored 21 points in the first quarter via a three-yard touchdown pass from Wilton Speight to Jake Butt, a 21-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Tyrone Wheatley, and a one-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill. Michigan added to its lead in the second with a four-yard touchdown run from De'Veon Smith, and a 23-yard field goal by Kenny Allen, which made the score 31\u20130 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Michigan added to its lead with a 27-yard field goal by Allen in the third quarter. Illinois responded in the fourth quarter with a 43-yard touchdown pass from Jeff George, Jr. to Malik Turner, and a two-point conversion pass from George to Zach Grant, before Michigan added the final points of the game via a 45-yard touchdown run from Karan Higdon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Illinois-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 22, 2016|date=October 22, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=400869676}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's honorary captain for the game was MLB Hall of Famer [[Hank Aaron]]. Michigan improved to 7\u20130 for the first time since [[2006 Michigan Wolverines football team|2006]]. Jake Butt recorded his fourth touchdown of the season\u2014the 11th of his career\u2014to gain sole possession of second second place on Michigan's list of career touchdowns by a tight end, four behind leader [[Jerame Tuman]] (15). Amara Darboh extended his streak of consecutive games with a catch to 27 and now holds sole possession of the sixth spot among Michigan leaders in the category. Michigan's defense held Illinois to 172 total yards, and without a passing yard in the first half. This was the fourth straight game that Michigan has held an opponent to less than 200 yards.<ref name=IllinoisNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===at Michigan State===\n{{see also|2016 Michigan State Spartans football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Michigan at Michigan State''' <br /> ([[Michigan\u2013Michigan State football rivalry|Paul Bunyan Trophy]])\n| Visitor = '''#2 Wolverines'''\n| Host = Spartans\n| V1 = 7 | V2 = 20 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 5\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 3 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 13\n| Date = October 29\n| Location = Spartan Stadium <br /> East Lansing, MI\n|TimeZone=EDT\n| StartTime = 12:01 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:46\n| Attendance = 75,802\n| Weather = 68\u00ba F, Overcast, WSW 11 MPH\n| Referee = Don Willard\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Bob Wischusen]], [[Brock Huard]] & [[Allison Williams (reporter)|Allison Williams]]\n|TVStation=ESPN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=MSU/><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan\u2013Michigan State Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 24, 2016|date=October 24, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161024aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=7:58|Team=MSU|Event=[[LJ Scott]] 5-yard run (Michael Geiger kick)|Score=MSU 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=4:30|Team=MICH|Event=Jabrill Peppers 3-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=Tie 7\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=12:19|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=9:24|Team=MSU|Event=Michael Geiger 52-yard field goal|Score=MICH 14\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=6:41|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 23-yard field goal|Score=MICH 17\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=:39|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 5-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 24\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=0:00|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 23-yard field goal|Score=MICH 27\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=14:42|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 45-yard field goal|Score=MICH 30\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=7:31|Team=MSU|Event=Monty Madaris 20-yard pass form [[Brian Lewerke]] (Michael Geiger kick)|Score=MICH 30\u201317}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=0:01|Team=MSU|Event=Donnie Corley 20-yard pass form Tyler O'Connor (Tyler O'Connor run failed)|Score=MICH 30\u201323}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=0:01|Team=MICH|Event=Jabrill Peppers defensive PAT return|Score=MICH 32\u201323|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 68\u201335\u20135\n| October 17, 2015\n| Michigan State, 27\u201323\n|}\nAfter its homecoming game against Illinois, Michigan traveled to East Lansing to face its in-state rival, the Michigan State Spartans, for the Paul Bunyan Trophy. Michigan State defeated Michigan 27\u201323 in the previous season after returning a fumbled snap for a touchdown with no time remaining in the game.<ref name=MSUNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Michigan 32, Michigan State 23|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 29, 2016|date=October 29, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/102916aaa.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan defeated Michigan State, 32\u201323, for its first win against the Spartans since 2012 and its first win at Spartan Stadium since [[2007 Michigan Wolverines football team|2007]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverines Take Back Paul Bunyan Trophy|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 29, 2016|date=October 29, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/102916aab.html}}</ref> Michigan State opened the scoring in the first quarter with a five-yard touchdown run from LJ Scott, which capped off an opening drive that lasted seven minutes and two seconds. Michigan responded with a three-yard touchdown run from Jabrill Peppers and then took the lead in the second quarter with a one-yard touchdown run from De'Veon Smith. Michigan State reduced Michigan's lead to four with a 52-yard field goal from Michael Geiger, but Kenny Allen answered with a 23-yard field goal for Michigan. Michigan scored twice in the final minute of the half with a five-yard touchdown run from Smith and another 23-yard field goal from Allen, which gave Michigan a 27\u201310 lead at half-time. Michigan extended its lead to 20 in the fourth quarter with a 45-yard field goal from Allen, and coasted from there. Michigan State reduced Michigan's lead to seven points with a 5-yard touchdown pass from Tyler O'Connor to Donnie Corley with :01 left on the clock. On an ensuing two-point conversion attempt, O'Connor fumbled the ball and Peppers returned it for a two-point conversion for Michigan to close out the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan-Michigan State Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=October 29, 2016|date=October 29, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869681}}</ref>\n\nMichigan improved to 8\u20130 for the first time since 2006. Michigan's 5\u20130 record in Big Ten play is the best start to conference play for Michigan since its 6\u20130 start in 2007. With three receptions today, Jake Butt passed Jim Mandich (119 catches) for the second-most receptions by a tight end in Michigan history. Butt now has 121 career catches.<ref name=MSUNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Maryland===\n{{see also|2016 Maryland Terrapins football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Maryland at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = Terrapins\n| Host = '''#2 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 3\n| H1 = 14 | H2 = 21 | H3 = 10 | H4 = 14\n| Date = November 5\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EST\n| StartTime = 3:35 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:09\n| Attendance = 110,626\n| Weather = Mid 60s, Sunny some clouds, SW 10\u201315 MPH\n| Referee = Jeff Servinski\n|TVAnnouncers=Steve Levy, Brian Griese & Todd McShay\n|TVStation=ESPN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Maryland/><ref>{{cite news|title=Maryland\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 31, 2016|date=October 31, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161031aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=9:50|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 34-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=1|Time=2:56|Team=MICH|Event=Wilton Speight 10-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=9:15|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 3-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=3:52|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 28\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=0:42|Team=MICH|Event=Jehu Chesson 33-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 35\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=10:00|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 29-yard field goal|Score=MICH 38\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=0:00|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 45\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=10:34|Team=UMD|Event=Adam Greene 37-yard field goal|Score=MICH 45\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=9:07|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 2-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 52\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=3:26|Team=MICH|Event=Kekoa Crawford 9-yard pass from John O'Korn (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 59\u20133|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 4\u20131\n| October 3, 2015\n| Michigan, 28\u20130\n|}\n\nAfter facing Michigan State, Michigan hosted the Maryland Terrapins. Maryland was led by Michigan's former defensive coordinator [[D. J. Durkin]]. In the 2015 contest, Michigan defeated Maryland, 28\u20130.<ref name=MarylandNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Michigan 59, Maryland 3|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=October 29, 2016|date=October 29, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/110516aae.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan won in another blowout, 59\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|title=Butt, Speight Set Records in Blowout Win|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 5, 2016|date=November 5, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/110516aaa.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a 34-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Darboh. Michigan added to its lead via a ten-yard touchdown run from Speight. Michigan added 21 points in the second quarter via a three-yard touchdown run from De'Veon Smith, a one-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill and a 33-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Chesson, which made the score 35\u20130 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Michigan added 10 points in the third quarter via a 29-yard field goal from Kenny Allen, and a one-yard touchdown run from Smith. Maryland opened the scoring in the fourth quarter via a 37-yard field goal from Adam Greene, for their only points of the game. Michigan responded with 14 points via a two-yard touchdown run from Smith, his third rushing touchdown of the game, and a nine-yard touchdown pass from John O'Korn to Kekoa Crawford.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maryland-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 5, 2016|date=November 5, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869685}}</ref>\n\nMichigan improved to 9\u20130 for the first time since 2006. Wilton Speight set a program record for the most passing yards in the first half with 292 yards. The previous record-holder was [[Denard Robinson]], who had 262 vs. Illinois in [[2010 Michigan Wolverines football team|2010]]. This was the first game the Wolverine offense featured a 300-yard passer (Wilton Speight, 362), a 100-yard rusher (De'Veon Smith, 114) and a 100-yard receiver (Jehu Chesson, 112) since October 19, 2013, vs. Indiana. Jake Butt became the program's all-time leader for receiving yards from a tight end (1,521), surpassing the previous record set by [[Jim Mandich]] (1,508). Michigan's defense combined for 13 tackles-for loss, tying a season record.<ref name=MarylandNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===at Iowa===\n{{see also|2016 Iowa Hawkeyes football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Michigan at Iowa'''\n| Visitor = #2 Wolverines\n| Host = '''Hawkeyes'''\n| V1 = 3 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 3\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 8 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 3\n| Date = November 12\n| Location = Kinnick Stadium <br /> Iowa City, IA\n|TimeZone=EST\n| StartTime = 7:12 pm\n| ElapsedTime = 3:19\n| Attendance = 70,585\n| Weather = 41\u00ba F, Mostly cloudy, S 4 MPH\n| Referee = John O'Neill\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Chris Fowler]], [[Kirk Herbstreit]] & [[Samantha Ponder]]\n|TVStation=ABC\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Iowa/><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan\u2013Iowa Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 8, 2016|date=November 8, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161108aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=1|Time=4:00|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 26-yard field goal|Score=MICH 3\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=8:56|Team=MICH|Event=Ty Isaac 7-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 10\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=6:31|Team=IOWA|Event=[[Jaleel Johnson]] safety|Score=MICH 10\u20132}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=1:27|Team=IOWA|Event=[[Akrum Wadley]] 3-yard pass from C. J. Beathard (C. J. Beathard pass failed)|Score=MICH 10\u20138}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=9:55|Team=IOWA|Event=Keith Duncan 25-yard field goal|Score=IOWA 11\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=9:35|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 51-yard field goal|Score=MICH 13\u201311}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=0:00|Team=IOWA|Event=Keith Duncan 33-yard field goal|Score=IOWA 14\u201313|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n|41\u201314\u20134\n| November 23, 2013\n| Iowa, 24\u201321\n|}\n\nAfter hosting Maryland, Michigan traveled to Iowa City, Iowa to face the Iowa Hawkeyes. This was the first meeting between the two schools since Iowa defeated Michigan 24\u201321 in 2013.<ref name=IowaNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: Iowa 14, #2 Michigan 13|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 12, 2016|date=November 12, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/111316aaa.html}}</ref>\n\nIowa upset Michigan, 13\u201314.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverines Fall on Final Kick|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 12, 2016|date=November 12, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/111316aae.html}}</ref> Michigan opened the scoring in the first quarter via a 26-yard field goal from Kenny Allen. Michigan extended its lead in the second quarter via a seven-yard touchdown run from Ty Isaac. Iowa responded with a Jaleel Johnson safety and a three-yard touchdown pass from [[C. J. Beathard]] to Akrum Wadley, which made the score 10\u20138 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Iowa took their first lead of the game via a 25-yard field goal from Keith Duncan. Michigan responded with a 51-yard field goal from Allen, to regain the lead, before Duncan scored the game-winning 33-yard field goal as time expired.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan-Iowa Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 12, 2016|date=November 12, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869690}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's 37 rushing scores are the third most for the team since [[1970 Michigan Wolverines football team|1970]], trailing only the 43 touchdowns scored by the [[1976 Michigan Wolverines football team|1976]] team and the 47 scored by the [[1971 Michigan Wolverines football team|1971]] team.<ref name=IowaNotes/> The game was similar to the [[1985 Michigan Wolverines football team|1985]] match-up between the two teams, when No. 1 ranked Iowa defeated No. 2 ranked Michigan, quarterbacked by now Michigan head coach Jim Harbaugh, on a game-winning field goal from [[Rob Houghtlin]] as time expired. After losses by No. 3 ranked [[2016 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]], and No. 4 ranked [[2016 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]] earlier in the day, and the loss by No. 2 ranked Michigan, this marked the first time since October 19, 1985 that Nos. 2\u20134 all lost on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iowa shocks No. 3 Michigan 14\u201313 off game-winning field goal|work=USA Today|first=Mark|last=Snyder|accessdate=November 12, 2016|date=November 12, 2016|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2016/11/12/iowa-hawkeyes-upset-michigan-wolverines-field-goal/93753536/}}</ref> In the days following the game, it was erroneously reported by blogger Brian Cook of the \"mgoblog\" fan website that Speight had endured a broken collarbone during the game and may be lost for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000739685/article/reports-michigan-qb-wilton-speight-has-broken-collarbone|title=Reports: Michigan QB Wilton Speight has broken collarbone|accessdate=November 21, 2016|date=November 14, 2016|publisher=[[NFL.com]]|author=Goodbread, Chase}}</ref> However, he returned for the game against Ohio State.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===vs. Indiana===\n{{see also|2016 Indiana Hoosiers football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Indiana at Michigan'''\n| Visitor = Hoosiers\n| Host = '''#4 Wolverines'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 3 | V4 = 0\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 3 | H3 = 17 | H4 = 0\n| Date = November 19\n| Location = Michigan Stadium <br /> Ann Arbor, MI\n|TimeZone=EST\n| StartTime = 3:35\n| ElapsedTime = 3:14\n| Attendance = 110,288\n| Weather = High 30s, Cloudy, rain/snow, NW 20\u201330 MPH\n| Referee = Jerry McGinn\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Dave Pasch]], [[Greg McElroy]] & [[Tom Luginbill]]\n|TVStation=ESPN\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=Indiana/><ref>{{cite news|title=Indiana\u2013Michigan Pre-game Notes|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 8, 2016|date=November 8, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/release/release_20161114aaa.pdf}}</ref>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=2|Time=8:48|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 28-yard field goal|Score=MICH 3\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=4:00|Team=IND|Event=Camion Patrick 2-yard run (Griffin Oakes kick)|Score=IND 7\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=9:40|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 33-yard field goal|Score=IND 7\u20136}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=5:21|Team=IND|Event=Griffin Oakes 24-yard field goal|Score=IND 10\u20136}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=4:02|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 34-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 13\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=0:29|Team=MICH|Event=De'Veon Smith 39-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 20\u201310|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n|55\u20139\n| November 14, 2015\n| Michigan, 48\u201341 <sup>2OT</sup>\n|}\n\nFollowing its game against Iowa, Michigan played its final home game against Indiana. Michigan defeated Indiana 48\u201341 in double overtime the previous season.<ref name=IndianaNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #4 Michigan 20, Indiana 10|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 19, 2016|date=November 19, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/111916aad.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan defeated Indiana, 20\u201310.<ref>{{cite news|title=8\u20130 at Home Behind Strong Senior Effort|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 19, 2016|date=November 19, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/111916aaa.html}}</ref> After neither team scored in the first quarter, Michigan opened the scoring in the second quarter via a 28-yard field goal from Kenny Allen. Indiana responded with a two-yard touchdown run from Camion Patrick, which made the score 7\u20133 in favor of Indiana at half-time. Michigan reduced Indiana's lead to one point via a 33-yard field goal from Allen. Indiana extended its lead in the third quarter via a 24-yard field goal from [[Griffin Oakes]]. Michigan responded with 14 unanswered points via two touchdown runs from De'Veon Smith, one from 34-yards, and one from 39-yards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indiana-Michigan Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 19, 2016|date=November 19, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869695}}</ref>\n\nMichigan improved to 10\u20131, achieving back-to-back double-digit win seasons for the first time since [[2002 Michigan Wolverines football team|2002]]\u2013[[2003 Michigan Wolverines football team|03]]. It is the 28th time in program history that Michigan reached 10 wins. Jim Harbaugh is one of only two coaches in program history to win 10 games in each of his first two seasons as head coach, joining [[Fielding Yost]] ([[1901 Michigan Wolverines football team|1901]]\u2013[[1902 Michigan Wolverines football team|02]]). Senior quarterback [[John O'Korn]] made his first start since the 2014 season. With two pass breakups against the Hoosiers, cornerback [[Jourdan Lewis]] upped his career total to 43 to tie [[Leon Hall]] (2003\u201306) for the most in Michigan history.<ref name=IndianaNotes/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===at Ohio State===\n{{see also|2016 Ohio State Buckeyes football team}}\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = Michigan at Ohio State <br />([[Michigan\u2013Ohio State football rivalry|The Game]])\n| Visitor = #3 Wolverines\n| Host = '''#2 Buckeyes'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 10 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 0 | VOT = 7 | VOT2 = 3\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 3 | HOT = 7 | HOT2 = 6\n| Date = November 26\n| Location = Ohio Stadium <br /> Columbus, OH\n|TimeZone=EST\n| StartTime = 12:00\n| ElapsedTime = 3:51\n| Attendance = 110,045\n| Weather = 43\u00ba F, Partly cloudy, W 10 MPH\n| Referee = Daniel Capron\n|TVAnnouncers=Chris Fowler, Kirk Herbstreit, Samantha Ponder, Tom Rinaldi\n|TVStation=ABC\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=OhioState/>\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|FirstEntry=yes|Quarter=2|Time=13:31|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 28-yard field goal|Score=MICH 3\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=4:03|Team=OSU|Event=[[Malik Hooker]] 16-yard interception return (Durbin Tyler kick)|Score=OSU 7\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2|Time=0:06|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 1-yard run (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 10\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=6:37|Team=MICH|Event=Khalid Hill 8-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=MICH 17\u20137}}\n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=3|Time=1:06|Team=OSU|Event=Mike Weber 1-yard run (Tyler Durbin kick)|Score=MICH 17\u201314}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=4|Time=0:01|Team=OSU|Event=Durbin Tyler 23-yard field goal|Score=Tie 17\u201317}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=OT|Time=0:00|Team=OSU|Event=J. T. Barrett 7-yard run (Tyler Durbin kick)|Score=OSU 24\u201317}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=OT|Time=0:00|Team=MICH|Event=Amara Darboh 5-yard pass from Wilton Speight (Kenny Allen kick)|Score=Tie 24\u201324}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2OT|Time=0:00|Team=MICH|Event=Kenny Allen 37-yard field goal|Score=MICH 27\u201324}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry|Quarter=2OT|Time=0:00|Team=OSU|Event=Curtis Samuel 15-yard run|Score=OSU 30\u201327|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overall Record\n! Previous Meeting\n! Previous Winner\n|-\n| 58\u201347\u20136\n| November 28, 2015\n| Ohio State, 42\u201313\n|}\n\nFollowing its home finale against Indiana, Michigan faced its arch-rivals, the Ohio State Buckeyes, in the 113th meeting of \"The Game\". In the previous meeting, Ohio State defeated Michigan for the fourth consecutive year, winning 42\u201313.<ref name=OhioStateNotes>{{cite news|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Ohio State 30, #3 Michigan 27 (2OT)|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=MGoBlue.com|accessdate=November 26, 2016|date=November 26, 2016|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/112616aaa.html}}</ref>\n\nMichigan lost to Ohio State 27\u201330 in double overtime. After neither team scored in the first quarter, Michigan opened the scoring in the second quarter via a 28-yard field goal from Kenny Allen. Ohio State responded with a 16-yard interception return from Malik Hooker. Michigan closed the scoring in the first half via a one-yard touchdown run from Khalid Hill, which made the score 10\u20137 in favor of Michigan at half-time. Michigan extended their lead in the third quarter via an eight-yard touchdown pass from Wilton Speight to Hill. Ohio State reduced Michigan's lead to three points via a one-yard touchdown run from [[Mike Weber (American football)|Mike Weber]], before Tyler Durbin recorded a 23-yard field goal as time expired in the fourth quarter to tie the game and force overtime. In overtime, Ohio State scored via a seven-yard touchdown run from [[J. T. Barrett]]. Michigan responded with a five-yard touchdown pass from Speight to Amara Darboh to force double overtime. In double overtime, Michigan scored via a 37-yard field goal from Allen, before [[Curtis Samuel]] recorded a 15-yard touchdown run to win the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan-Ohio State Box Score|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 26, 2016|date=November 26, 2016|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869650}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Adolph]] served as honorary captain for both Michigan and Ohio State. The game marked the 11th time that Michigan and Ohio State took the field both in the nation's top-five rankings; and is just the second time that both programs were ranked in the nation's top three. The other was the No. 1 vs. No. 2 matchup in [[2006 Michigan vs. Ohio State football game|2006]] at Ohio Stadium. The game also marked the first overtime in the Michigan-Ohio State rivalry. Michigan's defense recorded a season-best eight sacks against Ohio State. It is the program's most since posting nine against [[2007 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] on September 15, 2007. The Wolverines have recorded at least three sacks in each of the last four games. Wide receiver Amara Darboh surpassed the 2,000-yard receiving milestone in the contest. Darboh caught eight passes for 68 receiving yards, upping his career total to 2,026. Darboh has recorded a reception in 32 consecutive games, earning a share of the fourth spot among Michigan's all-time leaders in the category. He is tied with [[Marquise Walker]] (1998\u20132001).<ref name=OhioStateNotes/>\n\nThe Big Ten fined Head Coach Jim Harbaugh and the school $10,000 for violating their sportsmanship policy after he was critical of the officiating crew at a post-game press conference.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/more/la-sp-college-football-notes-20161128-story.html Michigan's Jim Harbaugh scolded for tirade] ''Los Angeles Times'', November 28, 2016</ref>\n\n'''Statistics'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Statistic\n!OSU\n!MICH\n|-\n|Total Yards\n|330\n|310\n|-\n