| {{sortname|Kenny|Allen|nolink=1}}\n| K\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|-\n| {{sortname|Ben|Bredeson}}\n| OG\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|-\n| {{sortname|Mike|McCray}}\n| LB\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|-\n| {{sortname|De'Veon|Smith}}\n| RB\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|-\n| {{sortname|Dymonte|Thomas}}\n| DB\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|-\n| {{sortname|Matt|Godin|nolink=1}}\n| DL\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n| data-sort-value=\"5\"| \u2013\n|-\n| {{sortname|Jehu|Chesson}}\n| WR\n| data-sort-value=\"5\"| \u2013\n| data-sort-value=\"4\"| Hon.\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"font-size:8pt; text-align:center;\"|Hon. = Honorable mention. '''Reference:'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/big10/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/misc_non_event/16fbawardwinners.pdf |title=2016 Big Ten Individual Award Winners |date=November 30, 2016 |publisher=Big Ten Conference |work=www.grfx.cstv.com |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2016 Big Ten Conference football season|Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football seasons]]\n[[Category:2016 in sports in Michigan|Michigan Football]]\n", "name_user": "Debartolo2917", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecruits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Michigan_Wolverines_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Cockburn", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film director\n| name         = Daniel Cockburn\n| image        = Director Daniel Cockburn leads a post-show Q&A (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Daniel Cockburn at [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF 2010]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1976}}<ref name=\"DAAD\">{{cite web |title=Cockburn, Daniel |url=http://www.berliner-kuenstlerprogramm.de/en/gast.php?id=1122&p=1 |website=[[DAAD Artists-in-Berlin Program|Berliner K\u00fcnstlerprogramm des DAAD]] |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Tweed, Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| education    = [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]], [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]]\n| alma mater    = [[York University]]\n| nationality  = Canadian\n| spouse       = Brenda Goldstein\n| years_active = 1999\u2013present\n| occupation   = [[Video artist]], [[film director]], [[performance artist]], [[professor]]\n| known for    = ''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]]''\n| awards       = [[Jay Scott Prize]]\n| website      = http://zerofunction.com\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Cockburn''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[performance artist]], [[film director]] and [[video artist]] who won the [[Jay Scott Prize]] in 2010 and the [[European Media Art Festival]]'s principal award in 2011 for his debut feature film ''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]].''<ref>\"Toronto Film Critics Association Awards\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 15 January 2011.</ref><ref name=\"QMUL\">{{cite web |title=Film Practice Research Fellowships |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/sllf/film-studies/research/film-practice-as-research/film-practice-research-fellowships/ |website=School of Languages, Linguistics and Film |publisher=[[Queen Mary University of London]] |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> Usually based in [[Toronto]] where he began his career in video, he has obtained several overseas academic or professional residencies and currently resides in [[London]].\n\n==Education and career in video and filmmaking==\n===Early short films and videos (1999-2007)===\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = I think I know how I justify asking people to give up their time to watch my work - I try to entertain them... I think that thinking is entertaining.\n| source = Daniel Cockburn (interview, October 2003)<ref name=\"Hirschmann\">{{cite news |last1=Hirschmann |first1=Thomas |title=Tranz Tech Profile |url=https://nowtoronto.com/art-and-books/art/tranz-tech-profile/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=Now |date=9 October 2003}}</ref> \n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\nOriginally from [[Tweed, Ontario|Tweed]], [[Ontario]], Cockburn graduated from [[York University]] with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in [[film studies]] in 1999, but felt \"dissatisfied with his own final project\", a 17-minute film that took him six months to finish; he decided to \"abandon all that stuff\", meaning big film productions heavy on stage design and light design, with sound engineers and a production manager, \"in order to make much simpler films based on his own writing.\"<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\">{{cite web |last1=Ortega de Mon |first1=Marcos |title=Directors Lounge: Daniel Cockburn |url=https://expcinema.org/site/en/directors-lounge-daniel-cockburn |website=Experimental Cinema |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> He discovered the [[experimental film]] community in [[Toronto]] \"and beyond,\" spending a decade making [[short films]] and video projects,<ref name=spotlight>\"In the spotlight: Daniel Cockburn showcases 'You Are Here' at Toronto film fest\". [[Canadian Press]], 13 September 2010.</ref> which were \"experimental, but which always had a strong narrative bent.\"<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite web |last1=Whyte |first1=Jason (interviewer) |title=Whistler Film Festival Interview - \"You Are Here\" director Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/feature.php?feature=3124 |website=eFilmCritic |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = He has a rare literary talent which he serves up with visual \u00e9lan, smart design sense and a playful philosophical project whose deeply lived roots is leavened throughout with humour. In fact, he's most serious when he's having fun. And even though his work appears as audio-visual feuilletons\u2014essayistic briefs, missives from the margins\u2014they possess an uncanny narrative order (though it is a narrativity steeped in the twentieth century, not the nineteenth).\n| source = [[Mike Hoolboom]]<ref name=\"Hoolboom2\">{{cite journal |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike |title=Experimental: Daniel Cockburn-Preliminary Notes |journal=Point of View Magazine |date=1 November 2005 |issue=60 [Winter 2005] |url=http://povmagazine.com/articles/view/experimental-daniel-cockburn-preliminary-notes |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\nCockburn released around three to six videos a year between 2000 and 2004. ''[[Metronome (film)|Metronome]]'' (2002) was his \"breakout hit\", attracting significant attention, an award, and an honourable mention.<ref name=\"Hoolboom\">{{cite book |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike (ed. and interviewer) |title=Practical Dreamers: Conversations with Movie Artists |date=2008 |publisher=Coach House Books |location=Toronto |page=20 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=n8eOKiK3llYC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=daniel+cockburn+hoolbloom+films+and+videos&source=bl&ots=Fhx2XDFHld&sig=ACfU3U1GvjzllOLgWR9lrSyaDAhEvKqbag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj9kMrb4uPkAhVRIjQIHefRDK84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=daniel%20cockburn%20hoolbloom%20films%20and%20videos&f=false  |accessdate=25 September 2019 |chapter=Daniel Cockburn: Smartbomb}}</ref> In 2003, [[Cameron Bailey]] declared Cockburn was \"Toronto's best new video artist\".<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite news |last1=Bailey |first1=Cameron |title=Cameron Bailey's Top 10 local filmakers |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/cameron-baileys-top-10-local-filmakers/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=25 December 2003}}</ref> Cockburn won more prizes for ''[[WEAKEND]]'' (2003) and ''Denominations'' (2004), the same year he worked in collaboration with [[Emily Vey Duke]] on ''Figure Vs. Ground'', and re-edited and released one of his earlier works in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.vtape.org/artist?ai=903 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nCockburn usually appeared in his own films, not exactly playing himself, but enacting the main (or only) character of his script: \"I am interested in this blank face without emotions. It becomes a projection surface for anything that happens in the film, like the Kuleshov Effect\", referring to the [[Lev Kuleshov|early Russian filmmaker]] who showed that the same head-shot could express different emotions according to adjunct edits in the film and he thus had a strong influence on [[Sergei Eisenstein]]'s theory of [[montage (film)|montage]]. \"And I decided I could do that myself; I didn't need an actor to make the kinds of films I wanted to make\".<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /> Sometimes, as in ''[[The Impostor (hello goodbye)]]'' (2003), he played multiple roles, or different aspects of the same role, which were also in some sense fictionalized versions of himself: \"I often perform in the work, in a mode that I started calling 'somewhere between fictional character and autobiography' when people started saying, 'that's not actually the way you think, is it?'\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn \u2013 \u2018Identity\u2019 \u2013 Artist Q&A |url=https://instigatearts.org/2016/10/04/daniel-cockburn-identity-artist-qa/ |website=Instigate Arts |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> Alissa Firth-Eagland, who curated an exhibition featuring his work in 2005, highlighted this feature of his art:<blockquote>Daniel Cockburn's videos are cleverly self-referential without being didactic. They are deliberately sleek and crafted, even produced, but it is Cockburn's performances within these productions that intrigue me most; his personae are disconcerting in their honesty and familiarity. I find there are many blind spots for me in all his onscreen characterizations. A notable mutability of portrayer and portrayed is evident in particular in his work ''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'': there's a mysterious blurring of fact and fiction. I am always left wondering how much of his onscreen personalities are, in fact, him.<ref name=\"Firth-Eagland\">{{cite web |last1=Firth-Eagland |first1=Alissa |title=Feats, might curated by Alissa Firth-Eagland |url=http://www.performanceart.ca/index.php?m=program&id=77 |website=FADO Performing Arts Centre |accessdate=15 October 2019 |date=2005}}</ref></blockquote>\nCockburn admits that \"over the years, his main characters became more and more influenced by autobiographical ideas.\"<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" />\n\n===Anthology and debut feature (2008-2010)===\nIn 2008, Cockburn won the K.M. Hunter Artists Award for Film & Video<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 K.M. Hunter Artist Award Winners |url=https://www.kmhunterfoundation.ca/artist_awards_pages/2008_award_winners.html |website=kmhunterfoundation.ca |publisher=K M. Hunter Foundation |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> ($8000),<ref>{{cite web |title=K.M. Hunter Artist Awards |url=https://www.kmhunterfoundation.ca/artist_awards.html |website=kmhunterfoundation.ca |publisher=K.M. Hunter Foundation |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> and began working on his first feature film.<ref name=Nayman>{{cite journal |last1=Nayman |first1=Adam |title=The Antisocial Network: Daniel Cockburn\u2019s You Are Here |journal=Cinema Scope |url=http://cinema-scope.com/cinema-scope-magazine/the-antisocial-network-daniel-cockburns-you-are-here/ |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====''You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different'' (2009)====\n{{Main|You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different}}\n In 2009, Cockburn was one of three directors invited to a six-month fellowship in Berlin ([[DAAD Artists-in-Berlin Program]]).<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn at IFFR |url=https://iffr.com/en/persons/daniel-cockburn |website=[[International Film Festival Rotterdam|IFFR]] |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> He returned to Toronto toward the end of the year with a curated programme of his films and videos,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Tracy Wright's fine, final performance |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/tracy-wrights-fine-final-performance/ |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=11 September 2010}}</ref> to launch a publication about his work.<ref name=\"PD\">{{cite web |title=You Are In A Maze Of Twisty Little Passages, All Different |url=http://pdome.org/2009/you-are-in-a-maze-of-twisty-little-passages-all-different/ |website=pdome.org |publisher=Pleasure Dome |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> The program included ''The Chinese Room'', a ten-minute work-in-progress excerpt from his upcoming feature.<ref name=\"PD\" /> Norman Wilner wrote a brief retrospective review of Cockburn's work prior to the event:<blockquote>Cockburn's work is strange and recursive and curious and enthralling, and sometimes all at once. In works like ''Metronome'' and ''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'', he considers life, death and dreams - and dreams about death - with a childlike fascination and an adult's sense of gravity. He'll ponder the collective illusion of time in ''Stupid Coalescing Becomers'', or investigate his suspicion that everything in the universe has doubled in size overnight in the aptly titled ''Nocturnal Doubling''. Calmly offering philosophical and metaphysical insights on the audio track, while evidence of his thesis plays out on the screen, he's both prankster and serious inquisitor; there's no way anything he's talking about is even plausible, let alone probable, but he's going to explore the possibilities as if it were.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Rocket man, space movies: Daniel Cockburn puts space movies in the universe of post-modern cultural collage |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/rocket-man-space-movies/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=December 4, 2009}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====''You Are Here'' (2010)====\n{{Main|You Are Here (2010 film)}}\nCockburn's first feature film has been presented at over forty [[film festivals]] worldwide, and compared to the works of [[Charlie Kaufman]], [[Jorge Luis Borges]], and [[Philip K. Dick]].<ref name=\"QMUL\" /> The film won both the [[Jay Scott Prize]] in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Incendies\u2019 wins the 2010 Rogers Best Canadian Film Award |url=https://torontofilmcritics.com/features/incendies-wins-the-2010-rogers-best-canadian-film-award/ |website=[[Toronto Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=19 January 2019 |date=January 13, 2011}}</ref> and the [[European Media Art Festival#Awards|EMAF Award]] in 2011,<ref name=\"EMAF\">{{cite web |title=And the winner is\u2026 |url=https://emaf2011.wordpress.com/2011/05/05/and-the-winner-is/ |website=EMAF |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> and with few exceptions, was received enthusiastically by critics. Marcos Ortega de Mon noted that in the film, finding and archiving material plays a big role in the narration:<blockquote>The activity of collecting seems to be a trap and source of obsession, but in other respects, it may also be a base for resistance, an escape from those powers that seem to have control over the claustrophobic situations his protagonists find themselves in, not only in the feature film but also in his shorts.<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Graduate studies and overseas residencies projects (2010- )===\nFollowing the release of ''You Are Here'' and the short ''Bad Idea Reunion'', Cockburn participated in the [[National Parks Project]], visiting [[Bruce Peninsula National Park]] with musicians [[John K. Samson]], [[Christine Fellows]] and [[Sandro Perri]],<ref>\"Film celebrates national parks through images and music\". ''[[Waterloo Region Record]]'', June 30, 2011.</ref> and also had two brief stints overseas as an [[artist-in-residence]] and a guest professor.{{refn|group=note|name=first|At the [[Impakt Festival]] in [[Utrecht]] in late November and early December 2010, Cockburn was the festival's artist in residence,<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn \u2013 Impakt Artist in Residence |url=http://impakt.nl/headquarters/works/2011-impakt-artist-in-residence-2011/daniel-cockburn-impakt-artist-in-residence/ |website=Impakt Festival |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> as part of the European Media Artists in Residence Exchange.<ref name=\"QMUL\" /> Over 2011 and 2012, Cockburn was a guest professor at the [[Braunschweig University of Art]].<ref name=\"Cockburn\">{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://zerofunction.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/05/Daniel-Cockburn-CV-Apr-2016.pdf |website=ZeroFunction Productions |publisher=Daniel Cockburn |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nCockburn's feature film script ''The Engineers'' won the [[Telefilm Canada]] Pitch This! prize ($15,000) at the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]], and was reported as in development with the [[Canadian Film Centre]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ng See Quan |first1=Danielle |title=TIFF deals inked for The Husband |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=16 September 2013 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2013/09/16/tiff-deals-inked-for-the-husband/ |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Cockburn returned to York University to begin working towards his [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree.<ref name=\"Cockburn\" /> During this period, he made the short films ''[[Sculpting Memory]]'' (2015) and ''[[The Argument (with annotations)]]'' (2017), the latter of which was also presented as his master's thesis,<ref>{{cite journal |title=York U talent featured at Toronto International Film Festival |url=http://yfile.news.yorku.ca/2017/09/07/york-u-talent-featured-at-toronto-international-film-festival/ |work=YFile |publisher=[[York University]] |accessdate=10 February 2019 |date=7 September 2017}}</ref> and made the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]'s annual [[Canada's Top Ten]] list in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Canada's Top Ten has some glaring omissions |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/special-screenings/canadas-top-ten-2017-has-glaring-omissions/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=6 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nBy the time ''The Argument'' was released, Cockburn had begun an artist-in-residenceship at [[Acme Studios]] and [[research fellow]]ship at the [[Queen Mary University of London]]'s School of Languages, Linguistics and Film in its pilot year.<ref name=\"QMUL\" /><ref name=\"FF\">{{cite web |title=Amateurs Club with Daniel Cockburn |url=https://forestfringe.co.uk/event/amateurs-club-with-daniel-cockburn/ |website=Forest Fringe |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> ''The Argument'', along with his most recent short films, including ''[[God's Nightmares]]'', are Canadian-British co-productions or else British productions.<ref name=\"British\">{{cite web |title=The Argument (with annotations) |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/the-argument-with-annotations |website=British Films Directory |publisher=British Council |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto goes British! |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/calendar/2017/toronto |website=[[British Council]] |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"TIFF2019\">{{cite web |title=Short Cuts Programme 06 |url=https://www.tiff.net/events/short-cuts-2019-programme-6 |website=tiff.net |publisher=[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]] |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BritishCouncil\">{{cite web |title=''God's Nightmares'' |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/gods-nightmares |website=British Films Directory |publisher=[[British Council]] |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"We\">{{cite web |title=Toronto 2019: UK films and co-productions so far announced |url=http://www.weareukfilm.com/news/toronto-2019 |website=We Are UK Film |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> During the residency, Cockburn researched the extension of lecture-performance practice into an expanded-cinema format involving multiple projections and live video feeds.<ref name=\"FF\" />\n\n==Performance art and related works==\n===Early performances (2005-2007)===\nIn March 2005, Cockburn presented ''Visible Vocals'', a typing performance for ''Feats, might'', a night of performance art by video artists curated by Alissa Firth-Eagland, presented by Fado and the [[Museum of Contemporary Canadian Art]]. In 2007, a set of two books and a CD was published by Parasitic Ventures Press \"to replicate the performance in book form.\"<ref name=\"Firth-Eagland\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Book launch for new publications from Parasitic Ventures Press |url=https://artmetropole.com/events/book-launch-for-five-new-publication-from-parasitic-ventures-pre |website=Art Metropole |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n''ALTOGETHER'' is an ensemble performance of music, movement, and monologue produced with the participation of York University students in 2007, the work explores \"semantic/somatic overlap and overload\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\"In There\" event schedule |url=http://www.yorku.ca/agyu/inthere.html |website=York University |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> It was also made into an [[installation art]] work as a commission from the university Art Gallery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Altogether documentation from Daniel Cockburn |format=video |url=https://player.vimeo.com/video/60862724 |website=[[Vimeo]] |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Performances on mistakes and failure (2009- )===\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = I promise to try to be sincere, and to be -- for the most part -- forthcoming about the ways in which I fail to be sincere.\nIt will perhaps be shown that my regrets constitute a parallel body of work... It could be described as a live version of one of my videos -- in which case it is possible that the presentation will make all the same mistakes the videos have.\n| source =  Daniel Cockburn, ''All The Mistakes I've Made''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Originalfassung #69: Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.generalpublic.de/nc/archive/eventsarchive/article/15/originalfassung-69-daniel-cockburn.html |website=generalpublic.de |accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\n====''All The Mistakes I've Made''====\nDuring his Berlin residency in 2009,<ref name=\"Martinson\">{{cite web |last1=Martinson |first1=Erik |title=Jenna Sutela, Daniel Cockburn, Frank Heath: Nice night for a walk |url=http://www.erik-martinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Nice-night-for-a-walk_Press-Release_The-Ryder.pdf |website=erik-martinson.com |accessdate=4 October 2019 |page=2 |format=press release |date=2017}}</ref> Cockburn developed an [[anti-art]]ist talk,<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\">{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn: Presentation \u201cAll the mistakes I\u2019ve made\u201d |website=[[Impakt Festival|Impakt]] |url=http://old.impakt.nl/wp-login.php?redirect_to=%2F2012%2Fchannel%2Freports%2Fdaniel-cockburn-presentation-all-the-mistakes-ive-made%2F |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> also called a \"lecture-performance\" about his professional mistakes as an artist, technical, aesthetic, and ideological.<ref name=\"PDAll\">{{cite web |title=All The Mistakes I\u2019ve Made |url=http://pdome.org/2013/all-the-mistakes-ive-made/ |website=Pleasure Dome |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> \"The art world is bursting with events where artists present an anthology of the highlights of their career to a slightly bored audience.\"<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\" /> Cockburn decided to turn this idea on its head with ''All The Mistakes I've Made'', examining to what extent his own inability to properly judge is representative of a \"negative trend\" in contemporary art and cinema, and supporting this argument with excerpts from his own work, and that of artists like [[Andrei Tarkovsky]] and [[Tim Burton]].<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\" /> The performance toured internationally,<ref name=\"Martinson\" /> described in 2013 as \"both playful and profound, personal and wide-reaching in its meditation on creative misguidance.\"<ref name=\"PDAll\" /> Cockburn performed ''All The Mistakes I've Made'' for several years.\n\n====''Heist Gone Wrong''====\nIn 2014, Cockburn put together a performance about [[failure]], ''Heist Gone Wrong'', which opened for the ''It wasn't supposed to be like this'' exhibition at [[Videofag]] in Toronto. The exhibition embraces \"the messy, mistaken, or misshapen,\" and \"explores how we might learn more from the times when things didnt work out, than from those times that they did.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=It wasn't supposed to be like this |url=https://www.blogto.com/events/it-wasnt-supposed-to-be-like-this/ |website=BlogTO |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Events |url=http://www.xpace.info/upcoming-events/ |website=Xspace Cultural Centre |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>  \n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Part scholarly monologue, part real-time essay film, and part solo theater, a bit like [[Spalding Gray]] with [[PowerPoint]]. ''All the Mistakes I've Made (Part 2)'' is about the cinema, and it is smart and amusing. Better still is its curt punch line, provided by none other than [[Paul Schrader]] \u2014 a sight gag worth the price of admission.\n| source =  Calum Marsh<ref name=\"Marsh\">{{cite news |last1=Marsh |first1=Calum |title=In Astoria, the First Look Festival Makes Heroes Out of Unsung Film Artists |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/04/in-astoria-the-first-look-festival-makes-heroes-out-of-unsung-film-artists/ |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=January 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\n====''All The Mistakes I've Made (part 2)''====\nSometimes also featuring a subtitle (''How Not To Watch a Film'') or alternate title (''How Not to Watch a Movie''), the performance is not, despite the titular suggestion, a follow up to ''All The Mistakes I've Made''; it is not necessary to have seen the original performance, as ''How Not To Watch A Movie'' is \"an independent, stand-alone work.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=How Not to Watch a Movie (or, All the Mistakes I\u2019ve Made, part 2) |url=https://homemcr.org/film/how-not-to-watch-a-movie-or-all-the-mistakes-ive-made-part-2/ |website=homemcr.org |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> It begins as a look at 1990s [[horror movies]] before \"spinning off into an autobiographical journey full of film references, over-interpretation and paranoia.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Matthew |title=FilmFear: six days of horror film previews and cult classics this Halloween at HOME |url=https://ilovemanchester.com/filmfear-manchester-horror-films-halloween/ |website=I Love Manchester |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> Cockburn argues against finding fault with [[continuity errors]], as he says in an essay dervied from the performance:<blockquote>We never would have noticed, if you hadn't pointed it out to us. IMDB users of the world: does it make you feel good to find mistakes in a world's construction? ... Film is joinery. That's what it is, what it does. So there's no point in getting indignant or superior when the joins aren't in line with what you think they ought to be.<ref name=\"CockburnHow\">{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Continuity Errors: An Appreciation |url=https://www.tiff.net/the-review/continuity-errors-an-appreciation |website=[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]] - The Review |accessdate=6 November 2019 |date=August 9, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nBoth ''Mistakes'' performance lectures have been presented to \"much acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Event Impakt Event with Daniel Cockburn: All the Mistakes I've Made pt 2 |url=http://emare.eu/news/impakt-event-daniel-cockburn-all-mistakes-ive-made-pt-2 |website=emare.eu |publisher=European Media Artists in Residence Exchange |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Current projects==\nAs of late 2019, Cockburn is adapting [[Mark Vonnegut]]'s memoir ''[[The Eden Express]]'' into a feature screenplay, and developing a new one-man multi-screen live show called \"All of the Other Agains\", which will premiere at the Flatpack Festival in [[Birmingham]] in 2020.<ref name=\"LAC\">{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=https://londonsartistquarter.org/artist-hub/users/danielcockburn/profile |website=London's Artist Corner |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn a number of interviews, Cockburn said that he struggled with a [[paranoia|paranoid]]-[[delusional disorder|delusional]] [[nervous breakdown|breakdown]]<ref name=\"Nayman\" /> during which \"everything I saw, read, and heard was some sort of message to me that needed to be decoded.\"<ref name=\"Kettmann\">{{cite news |last1=Kettmann |first1=Matt |title=You Are Here An Interview with Daniel Cockburn |url=https://www.independent.com/news/2011/feb/01/emyou-are-hereem/ |accessdate=18 January 2019 |work=Santa Barbara Independent |date=February 1, 2011}}</ref> It was a period of \"intense meaning-making ... I'd be looking at any text I'd encounter like a menu or road sign and I'd scramble the letters around and see if there were any different codes there that needed to be deciphered.\" After a long time, he realized that this behaviour, which was emotionally exhausting and troubling, had emotional underpinnings: \"It became something that wasn't just an enjoyable intellectual play. ... In a number of ways I worked through it, and part of that was figuring out what the emotional reasons were.\"<ref name=\"Klorfein\">{{cite web |last1=Klorfein |first1=Jason (interviewer) |title=A Conversation With Daniel Cockburn (YOU ARE HERE)/ |url=http://www.hammertonail.com/interviews/a-conversation-with-daniel-cockburn-you-are-here/ |website=Hammer to Nail |accessdate=17 January 2019 |date=May 11, 2012}}</ref> That experience \"stayed\" with him and worked its way into \"just about everything\" he wrote or directed, including his first feature film:<blockquote>''You Are Here'' is a compendium of characters dealing with the question of whether their life is just a series of random events, or whether there\u2019s some \"Great Code\" at the heart of it all. It's a cerebral concept, but when you're in the middle of it, it's scary and exciting and sometimes even funny, and that, for me, is the heart of the movie.<ref name=\"Kettmann\" /></blockquote>During postscreening question-and-answer sessions for ''You Are Here'', audiences often asked Cockburn what is religious beliefs were, and he answered: \"I don't know.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Interview with Daniel Cockburn, You Are Here |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/interview-with-daniel-cockburn-you-are-here/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=August 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDaniel Cockburn is currently living in [[London]], a Research Fellow in Film Practice at [[Queen Mary University of London]].<ref name=\"LAC\" /> He is married to [[installation art]]ist Brenda Goldstein.<ref name=\"Dixon\">{{cite news |last1=Dixon |first1=Guy |title=Daniel Cockburn, filmmaker |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/daniel-cockburn-filmmaker/article4258646/ |accessdate=25 September 2019 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCockburn has called fellow video artist Matthew C. Brown a friend. When Brown made a work for the One Minute Film & Video Festival titled ''This Thing Is Bigger Than the Both of Us: The Secret of String'' (2007), and would not tell Cockburn what it was about, he made one of his own with a view to hazarding a guess. Both were shown together at a screening of Cockburn's anthology film in Toronto by Pleasure Dome in 2009.<ref name=\"PD\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films and videos===\n;Early short films and videos (1999-2007){{refn|group=note|name=second|Based primarily on a chronological list compiled by [[Mike Hoolboom]].<ref name=\"Hoolboom\" /><ref name=\"Hoolboom3\">{{cite web |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://mikehoolboom.com/?p=58 |website=mikehoolboom.com |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{div col}}\n*''Doctor Virtuous'' (1999)\n*''Rocket Man'' (2000)\n*''monopedal Joy'' (2001)\n*''The Other Shoe'' (2001)\n*''IdeaL'' (2002)\n*''You Are in a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, all Different'' (2002)\n*''[[Metronome (film)|Metronome]]'' (2002)\n*''i hate video'' (2002)\n*''PSYCHO / 28 X 2''  (2002)\n*''Subteranea Gargantua (prelude)'' (2002)\n*''[[The Impostor (hello goodbye)]]'' (2003, commissioned by [[Vtape]] for The Colin Campbell Sessions)<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5452 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[WEAKEND]]'' (2003, commissioned by ''famefame'')<ref>{{cite web |title=''WEAKEND'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5453 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Denominations'' (2003)\n*''AUDIT'' (2003; second version, 2005)\n*''Figure vs. Ground'' (2004, with [[Emily Vey Duke]], commissioned by the 640 480 video collective for the VS. programme)<ref>{{cite web |title=Figure vs. Ground (with Emily Vey Duke) |url=http://zerofunction.com/figurevsground/summary-4/ |website=ZeroFunction |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Nocturnal Doubling]]'' (2004, commissioned by Friends of Rage Productions)<ref>{{cite web |title=''Nocturnal Doubling'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5771 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Chicken/Egg: The Williams Equation'' (2004)\n*''Continuity'' (2004)\n*''Stupid Coalescing Becomers'' (2004)\n*''Brother Tongue/Langue Fraternelle'' (2006)\n*''This Thing is Bigger Than the Both of Us: These Are Facts'' (2007)\n{{div col end}}\n;Anthology, feature, and later short films (2009- )\n{{div col}}\n*''[[You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different|You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different: Films and Videos by Daniel Cockburn]]'' (2009; ten of the above titles)\n*''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]]'' (2010)\n*''The Bad Idea Reunion'' (2010, for the [[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]] Talent Lab)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bad Idea Reunion |url=https://vimeo.com/26095115 |website=[[Vimeo]] |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Material'' (2011, commissioned by the [[National Parks Project]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Material |url=http://npp.spinshop.com/Individual%20Films/details/82238 |website=npp.spinshop.com |publisher=[[National Parks Project]] |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''My Godfather'' (2011, Impakt residency)<ref>{{cite web |title=My Godfather |url=https://vimeo.com/33754786 |website=Vimeo |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n*''[[Sculpting Memory]]'' (2015, commissioned by the [[National Film Board]])\n*''[[The Argument (with annotations)]]'' (2017; master's thesis)\n*''Repeat Viewing (After Hours)'' (2017)<ref>{{cite web |title=REPEAT VIEWING |url=https://shortfilms.org.uk/films/repeat-viewing-daniel-cockburn-2017 |website=ShortFilms.org.uk |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Pattern Recognition'' (2017, video essay commissioned by [[British Film Institute|BFI Digital]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Video essay: Pattern Recognition - using sound to scare at the movies |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/video-essay-thriller-sound-scare |website=British Film Institute |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Oller |first1=Jacob |title=The Art of Horror and Sonic Pattern Recognition |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/art-horror-sonic-pattern-recognition/ |website=[[Film School Rejects]] |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[God's Nightmares]]'' (2019)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Installations===\n*''ALTOGETHER'' (single-channel video), Art Gallery of York University (2007)\n*''I Can Feel It'' (3-channel video), Art Gallery of York University (2015, commissioned by AGYU Vitrines)<ref>{{cite web |title=Spring 2015 Newsletter: Out There Conducting the Refrain |url=http://theagyuisoutthere.org/everywhere/?p=4771 |website=AGYU Out There |publisher=The Art Gallery of York University |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2|group=note}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Monographs===\n*''Time Being: The Moving Images of Daniel Cockburn.'' Canadian Film Institute, 2014.\n===Articles===\n*Hoolboom, Mike. \"Experimental: Daniel Cockburn-Preliminary Notes.\" ''Point of View Magazine'' 60 (Winter 2005).\n*__________. \"Daniel Cockburn: Smartbomb.\" In ''Practical Dreamers: Conversations with Movie Artists''. Coach House Books, 2008.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Imdb name|1093572}}\n*[http://www.vtape.org/artist?ai=903 Daniel Cockburn] on Vtape\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockburn, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Film directors from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Canadian video artists]]\n[[Category:People from Hastings County]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film director\n| name         = Daniel Cockburn\n| image        = Director Daniel Cockburn leads a post-show Q&A (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Daniel Cockburn at [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF 2010]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1976}}<ref name=\"DAAD\">{{cite web |title=Cockburn, Daniel |url=http://www.berliner-kuenstlerprogramm.de/en/gast.php?id=1122&p=1 |website=[[DAAD Artists-in-Berlin Program|Berliner K\u00fcnstlerprogramm des DAAD]] |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Tweed, Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| education    = [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]], [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]]\n| alma mater    = [[York University]]\n| nationality  = Canadian\n| spouse       = Brenda Goldstein\n| years_active = 1999\u2013present\n| occupation   = [[Video artist]], [[film director]], [[performance artist]], [[professor]]\n| known for    = ''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]]''\n| awards       = [[Jay Scott Prize]]\n| website      = http://zerofunction.com\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Cockburn''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[performance artist]], [[film director]] and [[video artist]] who won the [[Jay Scott Prize]] in 2010 and the [[European Media Art Festival]]'s principal award in 2011 for his debut feature film ''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]].''<ref>\"Toronto Film Critics Association Awards\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 15 January 2011.</ref><ref name=\"QMUL\">{{cite web |title=Film Practice Research Fellowships |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/sllf/film-studies/research/film-practice-as-research/film-practice-research-fellowships/ |website=School of Languages, Linguistics and Film |publisher=[[Queen Mary University of London]] |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> Usually based in [[Toronto]] where he began his career in video, he has obtained several overseas academic or professional residencies and currently resides in [[London]].\n\n==Education and career in video and filmmaking==\n===Early short films and videos (1999-2007)===\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = I think I know how I justify asking people to give up their time to watch my work - I try to entertain them... I think that thinking is entertaining.\n| source = Daniel Cockburn (interview, October 2003)<ref name=\"Hirschmann\">{{cite news |last1=Hirschmann |first1=Thomas |title=Tranz Tech Profile |url=https://nowtoronto.com/art-and-books/art/tranz-tech-profile/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=Now |date=9 October 2003}}</ref> \n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\nOriginally from [[Tweed, Ontario|Tweed]], [[Ontario]], Cockburn graduated from [[York University]] with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in [[film studies]] in 1999, but felt \"dissatisfied with his own final project\", a 17-minute film that took him six months to finish; he decided to \"abandon all that stuff\", meaning big film productions heavy on stage design and light design, with sound engineers and a production manager, \"in order to make much simpler films based on his own writing.\"<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\">{{cite web |last1=Ortega de Mon |first1=Marcos |title=Directors Lounge: Daniel Cockburn |url=https://expcinema.org/site/en/directors-lounge-daniel-cockburn |website=Experimental Cinema |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> He discovered the [[experimental film]] community in [[Toronto]] \"and beyond,\" spending a decade making [[short films]] and video projects,<ref name=spotlight>\"In the spotlight: Daniel Cockburn showcases 'You Are Here' at Toronto film fest\". [[Canadian Press]], 13 September 2010.</ref> which were \"experimental, but which always had a strong narrative bent.\"<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite web |last1=Whyte |first1=Jason (interviewer) |title=Whistler Film Festival Interview - \"You Are Here\" director Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/feature.php?feature=3124 |website=eFilmCritic |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = He has a rare literary talent which he serves up with visual \u00e9lan, smart design sense and a playful philosophical project whose deeply lived roots is leavened throughout with humour. In fact, he's most serious when he's having fun. And even though his work appears as audio-visual feuilletons\u2014essayistic briefs, missives from the margins\u2014they possess an uncanny narrative order (though it is a narrativity steeped in the twentieth century, not the nineteenth).\n| source = [[Mike Hoolboom]]<ref name=\"Hoolboom2\">{{cite journal |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike |title=Experimental: Daniel Cockburn-Preliminary Notes |journal=Point of View Magazine |date=1 November 2005 |issue=60 [Winter 2005] |url=http://povmagazine.com/articles/view/experimental-daniel-cockburn-preliminary-notes |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\nCockburn released around three to six videos a year between 2000 and 2004. ''[[Metronome (film)|Metronome]]'' (2002) was his \"breakout hit\", attracting significant attention, an award, and an honourable mention.<ref name=\"Hoolboom\">{{cite book |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike (ed. and interviewer) |title=Practical Dreamers: Conversations with Movie Artists |date=2008 |publisher=Coach House Books |location=Toronto |page=20 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=n8eOKiK3llYC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=daniel+cockburn+hoolbloom+films+and+videos&source=bl&ots=Fhx2XDFHld&sig=ACfU3U1GvjzllOLgWR9lrSyaDAhEvKqbag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj9kMrb4uPkAhVRIjQIHefRDK84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=daniel%20cockburn%20hoolbloom%20films%20and%20videos&f=false  |accessdate=25 September 2019 |chapter=Daniel Cockburn: Smartbomb}}</ref> In 2003, [[Cameron Bailey]] declared Cockburn was \"Toronto's best new video artist\".<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite news |last1=Bailey |first1=Cameron |title=Cameron Bailey's Top 10 local filmakers |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/cameron-baileys-top-10-local-filmakers/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=25 December 2003}}</ref> Cockburn won more prizes for ''[[WEAKEND]]'' (2003) and ''Denominations'' (2004), the same year he worked in collaboration with [[Emily Vey Duke]] on ''Figure Vs. Ground'', and re-edited and released one of his earlier works in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.vtape.org/artist?ai=903 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nCockburn usually appeared in his own films, not exactly playing himself, but enacting the main (or only) character of his script: \"I am interested in this blank face without emotions. It becomes a projection surface for anything that happens in the film, like the Kuleshov Effect\", referring to the [[Lev Kuleshov|early Russian filmmaker]] who showed that the same head-shot could express different emotions according to adjunct edits in the film and he thus had a strong influence on [[Sergei Eisenstein]]'s theory of [[montage (film)|montage]]. \"And I decided I could do that myself; I didn't need an actor to make the kinds of films I wanted to make\".<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /> Sometimes, as in ''[[The Impostor (hello goodbye)]]'' (2003), he played multiple roles, or different aspects of the same role, which were also in some sense fictionalized versions of himself: \"I often perform in the work, in a mode that I started calling 'somewhere between fictional character and autobiography' when people started saying, 'that's not actually the way you think, is it?'\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn \u2013 \u2018Identity\u2019 \u2013 Artist Q&A |url=https://instigatearts.org/2016/10/04/daniel-cockburn-identity-artist-qa/ |website=Instigate Arts |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> Alissa Firth-Eagland, who curated an exhibition featuring his work in 2005, highlighted this feature of his art:<blockquote>Daniel Cockburn's videos are cleverly self-referential without being didactic. They are deliberately sleek and crafted, even produced, but it is Cockburn's performances within these productions that intrigue me most; his personae are disconcerting in their honesty and familiarity. I find there are many blind spots for me in all his onscreen characterizations. A notable mutability of portrayer and portrayed is evident in particular in his work ''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'': there's a mysterious blurring of fact and fiction. I am always left wondering how much of his onscreen personalities are, in fact, him.<ref name=\"Firth-Eagland\">{{cite web |last1=Firth-Eagland |first1=Alissa |title=Feats, might curated by Alissa Firth-Eagland |url=http://www.performanceart.ca/index.php?m=program&id=77 |website=FADO Performing Arts Centre |accessdate=15 October 2019 |date=2005}}</ref></blockquote>\nCockburn admits that \"over the years, his main characters became more and more influenced by autobiographical ideas.\"<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" />\n\n===Anthology and debut feature (2008-2010)===\nIn 2008, Cockburn won the K.M. Hunter Artists Award for Film & Video<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 K.M. Hunter Artist Award Winners |url=https://www.kmhunterfoundation.ca/artist_awards_pages/2008_award_winners.html |website=kmhunterfoundation.ca |publisher=K M. Hunter Foundation |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> ($8000),<ref>{{cite web |title=K.M. Hunter Artist Awards |url=https://www.kmhunterfoundation.ca/artist_awards.html |website=kmhunterfoundation.ca |publisher=K.M. Hunter Foundation |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> and began working on his first feature film.<ref name=Nayman>{{cite journal |last1=Nayman |first1=Adam |title=The Antisocial Network: Daniel Cockburn\u2019s You Are Here |journal=Cinema Scope |url=http://cinema-scope.com/cinema-scope-magazine/the-antisocial-network-daniel-cockburns-you-are-here/ |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====''You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different'' (2009)====\n{{Main|You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different}}\n In 2009, Cockburn was one of three directors invited to a six-month fellowship in Berlin ([[DAAD Artists-in-Berlin Program]]).<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn at IFFR |url=https://iffr.com/en/persons/daniel-cockburn |website=[[International Film Festival Rotterdam|IFFR]] |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> He returned to Toronto toward the end of the year with a curated programme of his films and videos,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Tracy Wright's fine, final performance |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/tracy-wrights-fine-final-performance/ |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=11 September 2010}}</ref> to launch a publication about his work.<ref name=\"PD\">{{cite web |title=You Are In A Maze Of Twisty Little Passages, All Different |url=http://pdome.org/2009/you-are-in-a-maze-of-twisty-little-passages-all-different/ |website=pdome.org |publisher=Pleasure Dome |accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> The program included ''The Chinese Room'', a ten-minute work-in-progress excerpt from his upcoming feature.<ref name=\"PD\" /> Norman Wilner wrote a brief retrospective review of Cockburn's work prior to the event:<blockquote>Cockburn's work is strange and recursive and curious and enthralling, and sometimes all at once. In works like ''Metronome'' and ''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'', he considers life, death and dreams - and dreams about death - with a childlike fascination and an adult's sense of gravity. He'll ponder the collective illusion of time in ''Stupid Coalescing Becomers'', or investigate his suspicion that everything in the universe has doubled in size overnight in the aptly titled ''Nocturnal Doubling''. Calmly offering philosophical and metaphysical insights on the audio track, while evidence of his thesis plays out on the screen, he's both prankster and serious inquisitor; there's no way anything he's talking about is even plausible, let alone probable, but he's going to explore the possibilities as if it were.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Rocket man, space movies: Daniel Cockburn puts space movies in the universe of post-modern cultural collage |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/rocket-man-space-movies/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=December 4, 2009}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====''You Are Here'' (2010)====\n{{Main|You Are Here (2010 film)}}\nCockburn's first feature film has been presented at over forty [[film festivals]] worldwide, and compared to the works of [[Charlie Kaufman]], [[Jorge Luis Borges]], and [[Philip K. Dick]].<ref name=\"QMUL\" /> The film won both the [[Jay Scott Prize]] in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Incendies\u2019 wins the 2010 Rogers Best Canadian Film Award |url=https://torontofilmcritics.com/features/incendies-wins-the-2010-rogers-best-canadian-film-award/ |website=[[Toronto Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=19 January 2019 |date=January 13, 2011}}</ref> and the [[European Media Art Festival#Awards|EMAF Award]] in 2011,<ref name=\"EMAF\">{{cite web |title=And the winner is\u2026 |url=https://emaf2011.wordpress.com/2011/05/05/and-the-winner-is/ |website=EMAF |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> and with few exceptions, was received enthusiastically by critics. Marcos Ortega de Mon noted that in the film, finding and archiving material plays a big role in the narration:<blockquote>The activity of collecting seems to be a trap and source of obsession, but in other respects, it may also be a base for resistance, an escape from those powers that seem to have control over the claustrophobic situations his protagonists find themselves in, not only in the feature film but also in his shorts.<ref name=\"Ortega de Mon\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Graduate studies and overseas residencies projects (2010- )===\nFollowing the release of ''You Are Here'' and the short ''Bad Idea Reunion'', Cockburn participated in the [[National Parks Project]], visiting [[Bruce Peninsula National Park]] with musicians [[John K. Samson]], [[Christine Fellows]] and [[Sandro Perri]],<ref>\"Film celebrates national parks through images and music\". ''[[Waterloo Region Record]]'', June 30, 2011.</ref> and also had two brief stints overseas as an [[artist-in-residence]] and a guest professor.{{refn|group=note|name=first|At the [[Impakt Festival]] in [[Utrecht]] in late November and early December 2010, Cockburn was the festival's artist in residence,<ref>{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn \u2013 Impakt Artist in Residence |url=http://impakt.nl/headquarters/works/2011-impakt-artist-in-residence-2011/daniel-cockburn-impakt-artist-in-residence/ |website=Impakt Festival |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> as part of the European Media Artists in Residence Exchange.<ref name=\"QMUL\" /> Over 2011 and 2012, Cockburn was a guest professor at the [[Braunschweig University of Art]].<ref name=\"Cockburn\">{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://zerofunction.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/05/Daniel-Cockburn-CV-Apr-2016.pdf |website=ZeroFunction Productions |publisher=Daniel Cockburn |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nCockburn's feature film script ''The Engineers'' won the [[Telefilm Canada]] Pitch This! prize ($15,000) at the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]], and was reported as in development with the [[Canadian Film Centre]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ng See Quan |first1=Danielle |title=TIFF deals inked for The Husband |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=16 September 2013 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2013/09/16/tiff-deals-inked-for-the-husband/ |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Cockburn returned to York University to begin working towards his [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree.<ref name=\"Cockburn\" /> During this period, he made the short films ''[[Sculpting Memory]]'' (2015) and ''[[The Argument (with annotations)]]'' (2017), the latter of which was also presented as his master's thesis,<ref>{{cite journal |title=York U talent featured at Toronto International Film Festival |url=http://yfile.news.yorku.ca/2017/09/07/york-u-talent-featured-at-toronto-international-film-festival/ |work=YFile |publisher=[[York University]] |accessdate=10 February 2019 |date=7 September 2017}}</ref> and made the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]'s annual [[Canada's Top Ten]] list in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Canada's Top Ten has some glaring omissions |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/special-screenings/canadas-top-ten-2017-has-glaring-omissions/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=6 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nBy the time ''The Argument'' was released, Cockburn had begun an artist-in-residenceship at [[Acme Studios]] and [[research fellow]]ship at the [[Queen Mary University of London]]'s School of Languages, Linguistics and Film in its pilot year.<ref name=\"QMUL\" /><ref name=\"FF\">{{cite web |title=Amateurs Club with Daniel Cockburn |url=https://forestfringe.co.uk/event/amateurs-club-with-daniel-cockburn/ |website=Forest Fringe |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> ''The Argument'', along with his most recent short films, including ''[[God's Nightmares]]'', are Canadian-British co-productions or else British productions.<ref name=\"British\">{{cite web |title=The Argument (with annotations) |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/the-argument-with-annotations |website=British Films Directory |publisher=British Council |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto goes British! |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/calendar/2017/toronto |website=[[British Council]] |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"TIFF2019\">{{cite web |title=Short Cuts Programme 06 |url=https://www.tiff.net/events/short-cuts-2019-programme-6 |website=tiff.net |publisher=[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]] |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BritishCouncil\">{{cite web |title=''God's Nightmares'' |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/gods-nightmares |website=British Films Directory |publisher=[[British Council]] |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"We\">{{cite web |title=Toronto 2019: UK films and co-productions so far announced |url=http://www.weareukfilm.com/news/toronto-2019 |website=We Are UK Film |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> During the residency, Cockburn researched the extension of lecture-performance practice into an expanded-cinema format involving multiple projections and live video feeds.<ref name=\"FF\" />\n\n==Performance art and related works==\n===Early performances (2005-2007)===\nIn March 2005, Cockburn presented ''Visible Vocals'', a typing performance for ''Feats, might'', a night of performance art by video artists curated by Alissa Firth-Eagland, presented by Fado and the [[Museum of Contemporary Canadian Art]]. In 2007, a set of two books and a CD was published by Parasitic Ventures Press \"to replicate the performance in book form.\"<ref name=\"Firth-Eagland\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Book launch for new publications from Parasitic Ventures Press |url=https://artmetropole.com/events/book-launch-for-five-new-publication-from-parasitic-ventures-pre |website=Art Metropole |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n''ALTOGETHER'' is an ensemble performance of music, movement, and monologue produced with the participation of York University students in 2007, the work explores \"semantic/somatic overlap and overload\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\"In There\" event schedule |url=http://www.yorku.ca/agyu/inthere.html |website=York University |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> It was also made into an [[installation art]] work as a commission from the university Art Gallery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Altogether documentation from Daniel Cockburn |format=video |url=https://player.vimeo.com/video/60862724 |website=[[Vimeo]] |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Performances on mistakes and failure (2009- )===\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = I promise to try to be sincere, and to be -- for the most part -- forthcoming about the ways in which I fail to be sincere.\nIt will perhaps be shown that my regrets constitute a parallel body of work... It could be described as a live version of one of my videos -- in which case it is possible that the presentation will make all the same mistakes the videos have.\n| source =  Daniel Cockburn, ''All The Mistakes I've Made''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Originalfassung #69: Daniel Cockburn |url=http://www.generalpublic.de/nc/archive/eventsarchive/article/15/originalfassung-69-daniel-cockburn.html |website=generalpublic.de |accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\n====''All The Mistakes I've Made''====\nDuring his Berlin residency in 2009,<ref name=\"Martinson\">{{cite web |last1=Martinson |first1=Erik |title=Jenna Sutela, Daniel Cockburn, Frank Heath: Nice night for a walk |url=http://www.erik-martinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Nice-night-for-a-walk_Press-Release_The-Ryder.pdf |website=erik-martinson.com |accessdate=4 October 2019 |page=2 |format=press release |date=2017}}</ref> Cockburn developed an [[anti-art]]ist talk,<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\">{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn: Presentation \u201cAll the mistakes I\u2019ve made\u201d |website=[[Impakt Festival|Impakt]] |url=http://old.impakt.nl/wp-login.php?redirect_to=%2F2012%2Fchannel%2Freports%2Fdaniel-cockburn-presentation-all-the-mistakes-ive-made%2F |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> also called a \"lecture-performance\" about his professional mistakes as an artist, technical, aesthetic, and ideological.<ref name=\"PDAll\">{{cite web |title=All The Mistakes I\u2019ve Made |url=http://pdome.org/2013/all-the-mistakes-ive-made/ |website=Pleasure Dome |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> \"The art world is bursting with events where artists present an anthology of the highlights of their career to a slightly bored audience.\"<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\" /> Cockburn decided to turn this idea on its head with ''All The Mistakes I've Made'', examining to what extent his own inability to properly judge is representative of a \"negative trend\" in contemporary art and cinema, and supporting this argument with excerpts from his own work, and that of artists like [[Andrei Tarkovsky]] and [[Tim Burton]].<ref name=\"ImpaktAll\" /> The performance toured internationally,<ref name=\"Martinson\" /> described in 2013 as \"both playful and profound, personal and wide-reaching in its meditation on creative misguidance.\"<ref name=\"PDAll\" /> Cockburn performed ''All The Mistakes I've Made'' for several years.\n\n====''Heist Gone Wrong''====\nIn 2014, Cockburn put together a performance about [[failure]], ''Heist Gone Wrong'', which opened for the ''It wasn't supposed to be like this'' exhibition at [[Videofag]] in Toronto. The exhibition embraces \"the messy, mistaken, or misshapen,\" and \"explores how we might learn more from the times when things didnt work out, than from those times that they did.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=It wasn't supposed to be like this |url=https://www.blogto.com/events/it-wasnt-supposed-to-be-like-this/ |website=BlogTO |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Events |url=http://www.xpace.info/upcoming-events/ |website=Xspace Cultural Centre |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>  \n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Part scholarly monologue, part real-time essay film, and part solo theater, a bit like [[Spalding Gray]] with [[PowerPoint]]. ''All the Mistakes I've Made (Part 2)'' is about the cinema, and it is smart and amusing. Better still is its curt punch line, provided by none other than [[Paul Schrader]] \u2014 a sight gag worth the price of admission.\n| source =  Calum Marsh<ref name=\"Marsh\">{{cite news |last1=Marsh |first1=Calum |title=In Astoria, the First Look Festival Makes Heroes Out of Unsung Film Artists |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/04/in-astoria-the-first-look-festival-makes-heroes-out-of-unsung-film-artists/ |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=January 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}\n====''All The Mistakes I've Made (part 2)''====\nSometimes also featuring a subtitle (''How Not To Watch a Film'') or alternate title (''How Not to Watch a Movie''), the performance is not, despite the titular suggestion, a follow up to ''All The Mistakes I've Made''; it is not necessary to have seen the original performance, as ''How Not To Watch A Movie'' is \"an independent, stand-alone work.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=How Not to Watch a Movie (or, All the Mistakes I\u2019ve Made, part 2) |url=https://homemcr.org/film/how-not-to-watch-a-movie-or-all-the-mistakes-ive-made-part-2/ |website=homemcr.org |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> It begins as a look at 1990s [[horror movies]] before \"spinning off into an autobiographical journey full of film references, over-interpretation and paranoia.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Matthew |title=FilmFear: six days of horror film previews and cult classics this Halloween at HOME |url=https://ilovemanchester.com/filmfear-manchester-horror-films-halloween/ |website=I Love Manchester |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> Cockburn argues against finding fault with [[continuity errors]], as he says in an essay dervied from the performance:<blockquote>We never would have noticed, if you hadn't pointed it out to us. IMDB users of the world: does it make you feel good to find mistakes in a world's construction? ... Film is joinery. That's what it is, what it does. So there's no point in getting indignant or superior when the joins aren't in line with what you think they ought to be.<ref name=\"CockburnHow\">{{cite web |last1=Cockburn |first1=Daniel |title=Continuity Errors: An Appreciation |url=https://www.tiff.net/the-review/continuity-errors-an-appreciation |website=[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]] - The Review |accessdate=6 November 2019 |date=August 9, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nBoth ''Mistakes'' performance lectures have been presented to \"much acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Event Impakt Event with Daniel Cockburn: All the Mistakes I've Made pt 2 |url=http://emare.eu/news/impakt-event-daniel-cockburn-all-mistakes-ive-made-pt-2 |website=emare.eu |publisher=European Media Artists in Residence Exchange |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Current projects==\nAs of late 2019, Cockburn is adapting [[Mark Vonnegut]]'s memoir ''[[The Eden Express]]'' into a feature screenplay, and developing a new one-man multi-screen live show called \"All of the Other Agains\", which will premiere at the Flatpack Festival in [[Birmingham]] in 2020.<ref name=\"LAC\">{{cite web |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=https://londonsartistquarter.org/artist-hub/users/danielcockburn/profile |website=London's Artist Corner |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn a number of interviews, Cockburn said that he struggled with a [[paranoia|paranoid]]-[[delusional disorder|delusional]] [[nervous breakdown|breakdown]]<ref name=\"Nayman\" /> during which \"everything I saw, read, and heard was some sort of message to me that needed to be decoded.\"<ref name=\"Kettmann\">{{cite news |last1=Kettmann |first1=Matt |title=You Are Here An Interview with Daniel Cockburn |url=https://www.independent.com/news/2011/feb/01/emyou-are-hereem/ |accessdate=18 January 2019 |work=Santa Barbara Independent |date=February 1, 2011}}</ref> It was a period of \"intense meaning-making ... I'd be looking at any text I'd encounter like a menu or road sign and I'd scramble the letters around and see if there were any different codes there that needed to be deciphered.\" After a long time, he realized that this behaviour, which was emotionally exhausting and troubling, had emotional underpinnings: \"It became something that wasn't just an enjoyable intellectual play. ... In a number of ways I worked through it, and part of that was figuring out what the emotional reasons were.\"<ref name=\"Klorfein\">{{cite web |last1=Klorfein |first1=Jason (interviewer) |title=A Conversation With Daniel Cockburn (YOU ARE HERE)/ |url=http://www.hammertonail.com/interviews/a-conversation-with-daniel-cockburn-you-are-here/ |website=Hammer to Nail |accessdate=17 January 2019 |date=May 11, 2012}}</ref> That experience \"stayed\" with him and worked its way into \"just about everything\" he wrote or directed, including his first feature film:<blockquote>''You Are Here'' is a compendium of characters dealing with the question of whether their life is just a series of random events, or whether there\u2019s some \"Great Code\" at the heart of it all. It's a cerebral concept, but when you're in the middle of it, it's scary and exciting and sometimes even funny, and that, for me, is the heart of the movie.<ref name=\"Kettmann\" /></blockquote>During postscreening question-and-answer sessions for ''You Are Here'', audiences often asked Cockburn what is religious beliefs were, and he answered: \"I don't know.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Interview with Daniel Cockburn, You Are Here |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/interview-with-daniel-cockburn-you-are-here/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=Now |date=August 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDaniel Cockburn is currently living in [[London]], a Research Fellow in Film Practice at [[Queen Mary University of London]].<ref name=\"LAC\" /> He is married to [[installation art]]ist Brenda Goldstein.<ref name=\"Dixon\">{{cite news |last1=Dixon |first1=Guy |title=Daniel Cockburn, filmmaker |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/daniel-cockburn-filmmaker/article4258646/ |accessdate=25 September 2019 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCockburn has called fellow video artist Matthew C. Brown a friend. When Brown made a work for the One Minute Film & Video Festival titled ''This Thing Is Bigger Than the Both of Us: The Secret of String'' (2007), and would not tell Cockburn what it was about, he made one of his own with a view to hazarding a guess. Both were shown together at a screening of Cockburn's anthology film in Toronto by Pleasure Dome in 2009.<ref name=\"PD\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films and videos===\n;Early short films and videos (1999-2007){{refn|group=note|name=second|Based primarily on a chronological list compiled by [[Mike Hoolboom]].<ref name=\"Hoolboom\" /><ref name=\"Hoolboom3\">{{cite web |last1=Hoolboom |first1=Mike |title=Daniel Cockburn |url=http://mikehoolboom.com/?p=58 |website=mikehoolboom.com |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{div col}}\n*''Doctor Virtuous'' (1999)\n*''Rocket Man'' (2000)\n*''monopedal Joy'' (2001)\n*''The Other Shoe'' (2001)\n*''IdeaL'' (2002)\n*''You Are in a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, all Different'' (2002)\n*''[[Metronome (film)|Metronome]]'' (2002)\n*''i hate video'' (2002)\n*''PSYCHO / 28 X 2''  (2002)\n*''Subteranea Gargantua (prelude)'' (2002)\n*''[[The Impostor (hello goodbye)]]'' (2003, commissioned by [[Vtape]] for The Colin Campbell Sessions)<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Impostor (hello goodbye)'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5452 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[WEAKEND]]'' (2003, commissioned by ''famefame'')<ref>{{cite web |title=''WEAKEND'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5453 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Denominations'' (2003)\n*''AUDIT'' (2003; second version, 2005)\n*''Figure vs. Ground'' (2004, with [[Emily Vey Duke]], commissioned by the 640 480 video collective for the VS. programme)<ref>{{cite web |title=Figure vs. Ground (with Emily Vey Duke) |url=http://zerofunction.com/figurevsground/summary-4/ |website=ZeroFunction |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Nocturnal Doubling]]'' (2004, commissioned by Friends of Rage Productions)<ref>{{cite web |title=''Nocturnal Doubling'' |url=http://www.vtape.org/video?vi=5771 |website=[[Vtape]] |accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Chicken/Egg: The Williams Equation'' (2004)\n*''Continuity'' (2004)\n*''Stupid Coalescing Becomers'' (2004)\n*''Brother Tongue/Langue Fraternelle'' (2006)\n*''This Thing is Bigger Than the Both of Us: These Are Facts'' (2007)\n{{div col end}}\n;Anthology, feature, and later short films (2009- )\n{{div col}}\n*''[[You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different|You Are In a Maze of Twisty Little Passages, All Different: Films and Videos by Daniel Cockburn]]'' (2009; ten of the above titles)\n*''[[You Are Here (2010 film)|You Are Here]]'' (2010)\n*''The Bad Idea Reunion'' (2010, for the [[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]] Talent Lab)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bad Idea Reunion |url=https://vimeo.com/26095115 |website=[[Vimeo]] |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''Material'' (2011, commissioned by the [[National Parks Project]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Material |url=http://npp.spinshop.com/Individual%20Films/details/82238 |website=npp.spinshop.com |publisher=[[National Parks Project]] |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n*''My Godfather'' (2011, Impakt residency)<ref>{{cite web |title=My Godfather |url=https://vimeo.com/33754786 |website=Vimeo |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n*''[[Sculpting Memory]]'' (2015, commissioned by the [[National Film Board]])\n*''[[The Argument (with annotations)]]'' (2017; master's thesis)\n*''Repeat Viewing (After Hours)'' (2017)<ref>{{cite web |title=REPEAT VIEWING |url=https://shortfilms.org.uk/films/repeat-viewing-daniel-cockburn-2017 |website=ShortFilms.org.uk |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Pattern Recognition'' (2017, video essay commissioned by [[British Film Institute|BFI Digital]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Video essay: Pattern Recognition - using sound to scare at the movies |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/video-essay-thriller-sound-scare |website=British Film Institute |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Oller |first1=Jacob |title=The Art of Horror and Sonic Pattern Recognition |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/art-horror-sonic-pattern-recognition/ |website=[[Film School Rejects]] |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[God's Nightmares]]'' (2019)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Installations===\n*''ALTOGETHER'' (single-channel video), Art Gallery of York University (2007)\n*''I Can Feel It'' (3-channel video), Art Gallery of York University (2015, commissioned by AGYU Vitrines)<ref>{{cite web |title=Spring 2015 Newsletter: Out There Conducting the Refrain |url=http://theagyuisoutthere.org/everywhere/?p=4771 |website=AGYU Out There |publisher=The Art Gallery of York University |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2|group=note}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Monographs===\n*''Time Being: The Moving Images of Daniel Cockburn.'' Canadian Film Institute, 2014.\n===Articles===\n*Hoolboom, Mike. \"Experimental: Daniel Cockburn-Preliminary Notes.\" ''Point of View Magazine'' 60 (Winter 2005).\n*__________. \"Daniel Cockburn: Smartbomb.\" In ''Practical Dreamers: Conversations with Movie Artists''. Coach House Books, 2008.\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Imdb name|1093572}}\n*[http://www.vtape.org/artist?ai=903 Daniel Cockburn] on Vtape\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockburn, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Film directors from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Canadian video artists]]\n[[Category:People from Hastings County]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n", "name_user": "ZarhanFastfire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Cockburn"}
{"title_page": "Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir", "text_new": "{{short description|Icelandic academic}}\n{{icelandic name|Hafd\u00eds|male}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = Hafdis Ingvars 2019.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            =\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        =\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| nationality        = [[Iceland]]ic\n| spouse             =\n| partner            =\n| party              =\n| relations          =\n| children           =\n| residence          =\n| alma_mater         =\n| occupation         = [[professor emerita]] in education at the [[University of Iceland]]\n| organization       =\n| religion           =\n| signature          =\n| website            =\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir''' is a  professor emeritus in education at the University of Iceland.<ref>[https://www.hi.is/staff/hei Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir. Professor emeritus]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref>\n\n== Professional experience ==\nHafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir completed her matriculation examination from [[Menntask\u00f3linn \u00ed Reykjav\u00edk]] (Junior College in Reykjavik) (1964), and obtained  her teaching certificate at Iceland University of Education (1965). She holds a BA in Danish and  History from the University of Iceland (1968). In addition to her BA studies, she taught at Hagask\u00f3li in Reykjavik. She later pursued graduate studies in Danish and literature at the  [[University of Copenhagen]] (1969\u20131971). After completing her studies, she returned to teaching at Hagask\u00f3li where she taught until 1981. She also taught at the [[Commercial College of Iceland]], holding a full-time position there until 1988. She then began working at the University of Iceland, initially as adjunct teacher and  teaching director. In 1997, she was appointed as an assistant professor. She holds a master's degree in Education  from the [[University of Reading]], [[England]] with emphasis on language learning and teaching (applied linguistics) (1993). She completed a doctorate in Education from the same university (2003). Hafd\u00eds was appointed as a professor in education in 2009 at the University of Iceland.<ref name=\"Hafd\u00eds\">{{Cite web|url=https://notendur.hi.is/hei/|title=afd\u00eds E. Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir. Uppeldis- og menntunarfr\u00e6\u00f0i}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nHafd\u00eds has engaged in numerous research projects related to teaching and education. In her research she has focused on teaching methods and teacher development with the aim of strengthening teacher growth. Her research can be divided into three overlapping fields: research into teachers\u2019 professional theories, research on teaching and research on teacher education.<ref name=\"Hafd\u00eds\" /> Her PhD dissertation reports a research into teachers\u2019 professional theories and how those influence their teaching: \u201cThe heart of the matter: the nature, use, and formation of teachers' subjective theories in secondary schools in Iceland.\u201d<ref>Skr\u00e1 um doktorsritger\u00f0ir \u00cdslendinga. [https://doktor.landsbokasafn.is/detail/1607 Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref> In order to strengthen teachers as professionals and, to develop approaches for that purpose. Hafd\u00eds has worked with and developed the concept of teachers\u2019 subjective theories and their connection to their teaching. She has also defined and worked with the concept of allies as an important construct to strengthen teachers' collaboration and cooperation.<ref name=\"Hafd\u00eds\" /> Hafd\u00eds has also researched the status of English and the teaching of English in Iceland in compulsory and upper secondary schools and universities. In the last decade, she has been engaged in longitudinal research (in collaboration with Professor [[Birna Arnbj\u00f6rnsd\u00f3ttir]]) on the status of English in Iceland.<ref>University of Iceland. (2018). [https://english.hi.is/news/the_impact_of_english_on_the_icelandic_speech_community The impact of English on the Icelandic speech community]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref>\n \nHafd\u00eds has taken part in many European development projects related to teaching, in addition to research projects on teacher education. She has worked enthusiastically on teachers' continuous education and has held many courses and workshops for that purpose. She has given lectures on her research at a great number of international conferences. Her writings have appeared in both Iceland and other countries in book chapters and peer-reviewed articles.<ref name=\"Hafd\u00eds\" />\n\n== Other work and projects ==\nHafd\u00eds has held various positions of confidentiality in Iceland and abroad, under the auspices of the Ministry of Education, Science and Culture and  the University of Iceland. She was on a collaborative committee on continuous education of upper secondary school teachers, where she represented the University of Iceland (1992\u20132009). The committee's function was to formulate policy on the continuing education of upper secondary school teachers and allocate funds to upper secondary schools for continuing education.<ref name=\"Hafd\u00eds\" /> Hafd\u00eds sat on a committee on European Teachers\u2019 Education 2010 after the Ministry of Education, Science and Culture nominated her for the period 2006 to 2008. The University of Iceland nominated Hafd\u00eds to sit on a committee, under the auspices of the Minister of Education, Science and Culture. The committee's function was to set out proposals on the future organisation of the curriculum for teachers 2005\u20132006.<ref>Menntam\u00e1lar\u00e1\u00f0uneyti\u00f0. (2006). [https://www.stjornarradid.is/media/menntamalaraduneyti-media/media/ritogskyrslur/framtidarskipan_kennaramenntunar.pdf Till\u00f6gur starfsh\u00f3ps um framt\u00ed\u00f0arskipan kennaramenntunar]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref> She was UI's representative on a national committee advising the Minister of Education, Science and Culture. The question was whether to introduce the use of the European portfolio in  language teaching (ETM) in Icelandic schools from 2002 to 2006.<ref>Menntam\u00e1lastofnun. [https://mms.is/namsefni/evropska-tungumalamappan-fyrir-framhaldsskolastigEvr\u00f3pska tungum\u00e1lamappan fyrir framhaldssk\u00f3lastig]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>Menntam\u00e1lastofnun. [https://mms.is/namsefni/evropska-tungumalamappan-fyrir-grunnskolastig Evr\u00f3pska tungum\u00e1lamappan fyrir grunnsk\u00f3lastig]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref> From 2003 to 2009, she sat on the executive committee of the International Study Association of Teachers and Teaching (ISATT).<ref>[https://www.isatt.net/ International Study Association of Teachers and Teaching]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref> This is an international association of researchers studying teachers and teaching. In addition, Hafd\u00eds sat on an advisory committee, The UK Council for Graduate Education,<ref>[http://www.ukcge.ac.uk/about-ukcge/ukcge.aspx UK Council for Graduate Education]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref> from 2006 to 2010. She was also one of the founders and the first chairman of the Language Teachers Association in Iceland (ST\u00cdL) from 1985 to 1989.<ref>P\u00e9tur Rasmussen. (2014). [http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=6089379 M\u00e9r hefur alltaf fundist danska svo fallegt tunugm\u00e1l]. M\u00e1lfr\u00ed\u00f0ur. T\u00edmarit Samtaka tungum\u00e1lakennara, 30(1): 5-9.</ref>\n\n== Acknowledgements ==\nIn 2016, Hafd\u00eds received an award from the international language teachers\u2019 association \u201cF\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale des Professeurs de Langues Vivantes\u201d (FIPLV) for her contribution to language teaching and research.<ref>ST\u00cdL \u2013 Samt\u00f6k tungum\u00e1lakennara \u00e1 \u00cdslandi \u2013 The Association of Language Teachers in Iceland. [http://stil-is.weebly.com/ Hei\u00f0ursver\u00f0laun FIPLV]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref>\n\n== Selected writings ==\n=== Articles ===\n*Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir (2006). [http://hdl.handle.net/1946/8638 \u201e\u2026eins og \u00fever geit \u00ed gir\u00f0ingu\u201c Vi\u00f0horf kennara til breytinga \u00e1 kennsluh\u00e1ttum]. In \u00dalfar Hauksson (Ritstj.), Ranns\u00f3knir \u00ed f\u00e9lagsv\u00edsindum VII (pp.&nbsp;351\u2013364). Reykjav\u00edk: H\u00e1sk\u00f3la\u00fatg\u00e1fan.  \n*Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir (2013). [https://www.degruyter.com/view/j/jelf.2013.2.issue-1/jelf-2013-0006/jelf-2013-0006.xml ELF and academic writing: a perspective from the Expanding Circle]. Journal of English as a Lingua Franca. JELF. De Gruyter.\n*Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir (2018). [http://netla.hi.is/serrit/2018/framhaldskolinn_brennidepli/03.pdf Kennsluh\u00e6ttir spegla\u00f0ir \u00ed lj\u00f3si sj\u00e1lfr\u00e6\u00f0is: Vir\u00f0ing, \u00e1byrg\u00f0 og traust]. Netla \u2013 Veft\u00edmarit um uppeldi og menntun. S\u00e9rrit 2018 \u2013 Framhaldsk\u00f3linn \u00ed brennidepli. Menntav\u00edsindasvi\u00f0 H\u00e1sk\u00f3la \u00cdslands, pp.&nbsp;1\u201314.\n\n=== Books ===\n*Birna  Arnbj\u00f6rnsd\u00f3ttir og Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir (ritstj.) (2007). [http://haskolautgafan.hi.is/teaching_and_learning_english_in_iceland Teaching and learning English in Iceland. In honour of Au\u00f0ur Torfad\u00f3ttir]. Reykjav\u00edk: Stofnun Vigd\u00edsar Finnbogad\u00f3ttur/H\u00e1sk\u00f3la\u00fatg\u00e1fan\n*Birna Arnbj\u00f6rnsd\u00f3ttir og Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir (eds.). (2017). [https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-319-67804-7 Language Development across the Life Span: The Impact of English on Education and Work in Iceland].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:University of Iceland faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iceland alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Copenhagen alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Icelandic women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Icelandic academic}}\n{{icelandic name|Hafd\u00eds|male}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = Hafdis Ingvars 2019.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            =\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        =\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| nationality        = [[Iceland]]ic\n| spouse             =\n| partner            =\n| party              =\n| relations          =\n| children           =\n| residence          =\n| alma_mater         =\n| occupation         = [[professor emerita]] in education at the [[University of Iceland]]\n| organization       =\n| religion           =\n| signature          =\n| website            =\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir''' is a  professor emeritus in education at the University of Iceland.<ref>[https://www.hi.is/staff/hei Hafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir. Professor emeritus]. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref>\n\n== Professional experience ==\nHafd\u00eds Ingvarsd\u00f3ttir completed her matriculation examination from [[Menntask\u00f3linn \u00ed Reykjav\u00edk]] (Junior College in Reykjavik) (1964), and obtained  her teaching certificate at Iceland University of Education (1965). She holds a BA in Danish and  History from the University of Iceland (1968). In addition to her BA studies, she taught at Hagask\u00f3li in Reykjavik. She later pursued graduate studies in Danish and literature at the  [[University of Copenhagen]] (1969\u20131971). After completing her studies, she returned to teaching at Hagask\u00f3li where she taught until 1981. She also taught at the [[Commercial College of Iceland]], holding a full-time position there until 1988. She then began working at the University of Iceland, initially as adjunct teacher and  tea